(141, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>Casting for <em>Ida&nbsp;</em>proved very&nbsp;difficult. Director Pawel Pawlikowski recounts that he spent severalm months searching through theatre companies and dramas schools throughout Poland in order to find his "Ida."&nbsp;&nbsp;He auditioned approximately&nbsp;400 actors, but none of them felt right to him. Pawlikowski&nbsp;eventually discovered&nbsp;Agata Trzebuchowska by spotting&nbsp;her reading a book&nbsp;in a cafe downstairs from where&nbsp;Pawlikowski lived in Warsaw. A&nbsp;philosophy and culture studies student at Warsaw University, Agata had no acting experience. Reportedly, she had never shown any desire to act before either, and according to&nbsp;Pawlikowski, a "complete atheist and a principled one."</p>\n\n<p>The sales agents tasked with selling&nbsp;<em>Ida</em>&nbsp;around the world were expressed reluctance to&nbsp;cast her&nbsp;and&nbsp;asked&nbsp;Pawlikowski to cast a "proper" actress.&nbsp;After viewing the first week&#39;s rushes, they&nbsp;believed&nbsp;that she did not have any emotional range, but&nbsp;Pawlikowski believed he had the right person precisely because she was very calm, quiet and grounded. To&nbsp;Pawlikowski, this was a character who knew how to listen and think before speaking - everything was to be internalized, not emoted openly.</p>', 'none', 'Agata Trzebuchowska, who had no prior acting experience, was discovered in a cafe, reading a book.', 'none', 'Agata Trzebuchowska\nCasting\nIda\nPaweł Pawlikowski', 'xhtml', 'ida1.jpg', 'none', '[138] [ida] Ida', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(139, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>[SPOILERS]</p>\n\n<p>According to <em>Birdman&nbsp;</em>screenwriter Alex Dinelaris,&nbsp;conceptually the original ending of <em>Birdman</em>&nbsp;would have looped the film back to the beginning.</p>\n\n<p>Following the climactic scene where Riggan Thomson (Michael Keaton) shoots himself&nbsp;and the audience erupts in&nbsp;thunderous applause, we&#39;d move forward in time and see Thomson and either James Lipton or Charlie Rose on stage, discussing the&nbsp;ecstatic review Tabitha Dickinson&nbsp;(Lindsay Duncan) had written for that performance. The camera then would continue to move backstage, eventually landing back at the dressing room where Johnny Depp would be sitting in front of the mirror and putting on the same curly wig that Thomson had worn earlier. A poster of&nbsp;<em>Pirates of the Caribbean 5</em>&nbsp;would be visible in the background, and over the soundtrack, we&#39;d hear Depp&#39;s inner thoughts, speaking in Jack Sparrow&#39;s voice, "What the fuck are we doing here, mate?"</p>\n\n<p>This ending was never shot because Depp wouldn&#39;t agree to it and because Disney wouldn&#39;t clear usage of their film&#39;s poster.</p>', 'none', 'The original ending of "Birdman" would have involved Johnny Depp and "Pirates of the Caribbean."', 'none', '', 'xhtml', 'johnny-depp-pirates-of-the-caribbean.jpg', 'none', '[6] [birdman] Birdman', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(140, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>Director&nbsp;Pawe&#322;&nbsp;Pawlikowski made the decision early on to shoot <em>Ida</em>&nbsp;in black &amp; white. His British&nbsp;producer was initially reluctant to make a film this way, reportedly telling the director that it would make the project look like a student film, but&nbsp;Pawlikowski was insistent,&nbsp;believing&nbsp;it was the right choice for the material as well as for the look that he had in mind.</p>\n\n<p>While shooting tests with different lenses and his costumed actresses,&nbsp;Pawlikowski decided to shoot in the square-like&nbsp;Academy ratio - once the standard aspect ratio for motion pictures until the 1950&#39;s and later the standard ratio for television programming until the 2000&#39;s. Part of it came out of an idea to frame each shot so that the bodies of his characters would not dominate the compositions, and eventually he came to the aesthetic he used for the film, where the camera would often be tilted up, leaving a lot of space above their heads. In Academy ratio, which gave a tighter framing to the sides, the space directly over the characters was accentuated even further. To Pawlikowski, the result was&nbsp;completely right as it made everyone look&nbsp;"lost in space."</p>', 'none', 'The film was shot in black & white with a standard Academy aspect ratio (1.37:1).', 'none', 'Aspect ratio\nCinematography\nComposition\nIda', 'xhtml', 'Ida_31.jpg', 'none', '[138] [ida] Ida', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(142, 1, 2, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', NULL, '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', 'tv-boardwalk-empire-outlaws-kings-poster-SC3051.jpg', 'none', '5', 'none', '56', 'none', 'Terence Winter, based on "Boardwalk Empire: The Birth, High Times, and Corruption of Atlantic City" by Nelson Johnson', 'none', 'Terence Winter, Martin Scorsese, Mark Wahlberg, Tim Van Patten, Howard Korder, Stephen Levinson', 'none', 'Steve Buscemi\nMichael Pitt\nKelly Macdonald\nMichael Shannon\nShea Whigham\nAleksa Palladino\nMichael Stuhlbarg\nStephen Graham\nVincent Piazza\nPaz de la Huerta\nMichael Kenneth Williams\nAnthony Laciura\nPaul Sparks\nDabney Coleman\nJack Huston\nGretchen Mol\nCharlie Cox\nBobby Cannavale\nRon Livingston\nJeffrey Wright', 'xhtml', 'HBO', 'none', '93% (Season 1),  88% (Season 2),  87% (Season 3),  96% (Season 4), 88% (Season 5)', 'none', '88% (Season 1),  81% (Season 2),  76% (Season 3),  77% (Season 4), 83% (Season 5)', 'none', 'http://www.hbo.com/boardwalk-empire', 'none', '<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/SPlBxJs3npQ" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'none', '<p>Season 1:&nbsp;Atlantic City in the 1920s is the setting for the series based on the book by Nelson Johnson about how the city turned into the infamous gambling locale.</p>\n\n<p>Season 2:&nbsp;After a successful election of his pick for Mayor, Nucky Thompson (Steve Buscemi) comes under investigation for voter fraud and soon finds his position tenuous as his family and friends turn against him.</p>\n\n<p>Season 3:&nbsp;The third season opens with Nucky Thompson celebrating the countdown to 1923. However, trouble brews as Gyp Rosetti (Bobby Cannavale), a mobster from Brooklyn, who disagrees with some of Nucky&#39;s decisions.</p>\n\n<p>Season 4:&nbsp;Season four picks up in 1924 and Nucky has new problems in the form of Valentin Narcisse (Jeffrey Wright) and FBI Agent Loren Knox (Brian Geraghty). Patricia Arquette joins the cast as a speakeasy owner named Sally Wheet.</p>\n\n<p>Season 5:&nbsp;The final season of the drama picks up in 1931 as Nucky plans life after Prohibition.</p>', 'none', '1', 'none', 'Atlantic City\nCable television\nGambling\nGangster films\nHBO\nMartin Scorsese\nProhibition\nSteve Buscemi\nTerence Winter', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(143, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>No. Creator Terence Winter wanted the setting and context to be as detailed and as faithful as possible to the non-fiction work that inspired the show, but the plot and characters are strictly fiction, even when they draw from real-life characters. <a href="http://www.wired.com/2012/09/tv-fact-checkers-boardwalk-empire/all/">As Winter told <em>Wired</em></a>, &ldquo;I was inspired to fictionalize as many people as possible because of Deadwood, which I loved&hellip;I knew we had a few people &mdash; Al Capone, Arnold Rothstein, Lucky Luciano &mdash; who I knew I could not deviate their major life arcs. I&rsquo;m not going to kill Capone off in 1925. The guy lived till the &rsquo;40s. Everywhere along the line, whenever I felt I could fictionalize a character, I would, starting with Nucky.I didn&rsquo;t want to be beholden to the actual Nucky Johnson&rsquo;s life, because my Nucky I would like to have do things that the real Nucky probably didn&rsquo;t do. Again, it&rsquo;s partly to be able to surprise the audience, and partly because I don&rsquo;t know if the real Nucky has relatives that are still living who are going to watch and say, &lsquo;My uncle never murdered nine people&rsquo; or whatever I want to have my guy do.&rdquo;</p>', 'none', 'Creator Terence Winter wanted the show''s production to be as detailed and as faithful as possible to the non-fiction book that inspired it.', 'none', 'Atlantic City\nCable television\nHBO\nProhibition\nTerence Winter', 'xhtml', 'Boardwalk-Empire-Anastasia-1-04-boardwalk-empire-30062700-1280-720.jpg', 'none', '[142] [boardwalk-empire] Boardwalk Empire', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(144, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p><a href="http://www.wired.com/2012/09/tv-fact-checkers-boardwalk-empire/all/">Edward McGinty, who not only plays Al Boyd in the show but is also head historical researcher and consultant, told <em>Wired</em></a> that &ldquo;the first season was more about building the world. It was a lot of broad strokes. It was a lot of really just getting the show and the world built and the audience to see what this world was. That was a lot of photo research and that type of thing. And then, it became more specific as it went on. I would do a lot more really specific medical and law research, to the point I was like, &lsquo;I could probably be a lawyer in 1921.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>\n\n<p>During the script writing process, the writers will have their consultants in the same room, answering their questions about historical details. The same consultants would continuously look through the written material during every step of the production, notifying the creative team of any inaccuracies, even through post-production. Consultants would often give directors visual guides, particularly historical photos, not only to maintain accuracy but consistency through the entire show.</p>', 'none', 'Edward McGinty not only plays Al Boyd in the show but is also head historical researcher and consultant.', 'none', 'Boardwalk Empire\nCable television\nHBO\nHistorical accuracy\nProhibition', 'xhtml', 'boardwalk_empire_image-1.jpg', 'none', '[142] [boardwalk-empire] Boardwalk Empire', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(145, 1, 2, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', NULL, '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', 'Season_1_AMC_Poster.jpg', 'none', '5', 'none', '62', 'none', 'Vince Gilligan', 'none', 'Vince Gilligan, Mark Johnson, Michelle MacLaren', 'none', 'Bryan Cranston\nAnna Gunn\nAaron Paul\nDean Norris\nBetsy Brandt\nRJ Mitte\nBob Odenkirk\nGiancarlo Esposito\nJonathan Banks\nLaura Fraser\nJesse Plemons', 'xhtml', 'AMC', 'none', '78 (Season 1), 100 (Seasons 2-5)', 'none', '74 (Season 1), 85 (Season 2), 89 (Season 3), 96 (Season 4), 99 (Season 5)', 'none', 'http://www.amctv.com/shows/breaking-bad', 'none', '<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/T3dpghfRBHE" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'none', '<p>A high school chemistry teacher is diagnosed with terminal lung cancer and resorts to selling methamphetamine to provide for his family when he is dead.</p>', 'none', '1', 'none', 'AMC\nBryan Cranston\nCable television\nCrime\nDrama\nDrug dealing\nVince Gilligan', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(147, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>Vince Gilligan has said that the larger lesson of the series is that "actions have consequences,&rdquo; and often cites examples within the show, such as an airplane collision, as symbolizing the damage Walter White&rsquo;s actions have brought upon those around him. However, many critics, <a href="http://grantland.com/features/bad-decisions/">including Chuck Klosterman</a>, have focused on how much most audience members will side with White, even as he continues his downward slide in moral corruption. Many of these arguments reflect what&rsquo;s been written about Alfred Hitchcock, particularly his film <em>Psycho</em>, and how audience sympathies can be manipulated so that they have no relation to the actual moral consequences of a character&rsquo;s actions.</p>\n\n<p>&ldquo;<em>Breaking Bad</em> is not a situation in which the characters&rsquo; morality is static or contradictory or colored by the time frame,&rdquo; says Klosterman. &ldquo;Instead, it suggests that morality is continually a personal choice...what we see in <em>Breaking Bad</em> is a person who started as one type of human and decides to become something different&hellip;And because we were introduced to this man in a way that made him impossible to dislike, the audience is placed in the curious position of continuing to root for an individual who&rsquo;s no longer good&hellip;this is a series in which the main character has actively become evil, but we still want him to succeed.&rdquo;</p>', 'none', 'Vince Gilligan has said that the larger lesson of the series is that "actions have consequences."', 'none', 'AMC\nBreaking Bad\nCable television\nMorality\nVince Gilligan', 'xhtml', 'Season_2_promo_pic_4.jpg', 'none', '[145] [breaking-bad] Breaking Bad', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(146, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>In the final scene of one episode titled &ldquo;Madrigal,&rdquo; Walter White says that "There&#39;s no better reason than family.&rdquo; <a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2012/07/on-breaking-bad-family-is-a-motivation-and-a-liability/260216/">Scott Meslow of <em>The Atlantic</em> singled that moment out</a> as &ldquo;a sentiment that could serve as an statement of purpose for [that episode]&mdash;and perhaps the entire series&mdash;which has seen virtually every character betray their morals and their best judgment in an attempt to protect the ones they love the most.&rdquo;</p>\n\n<p>The whole set-up for the series revolves around Walt&rsquo;s desire to provide for his family after he eventually succumbs to cancer. This turns him to a life of crime, cooking crystal meth. When he tries to go back to an honest life because his wife leaves him over his criminal activity, he changes his mind because someone convinces him of his familial obligation to provide for his family, even when they&rsquo;ve turned their backs to him.</p>\n\n<p>Every relationship in the show seems to have some familial basis. Walt&rsquo;s relationship with Jesse Pinkman is shaded by a surrogate father-son dynamic. (At one point, he even lies and claims Jesse is his nephew when he crosses paths with a figure from Jesse&rsquo;s personal life)</p>\n\n<p>Even the violent criminals in the show are defined by their familiar connections, often reflecting the familial model for criminal organizations seen in so many films and television shows going back to <em>The Godfather</em>. One pivotal moment even finds Walt surviving a near-death experience simply because his would-be executioner spares him out of familial duty, one that involve his own blood relatives and not Walt&rsquo;s.</p>\n\n<p>It&rsquo;s not until the final episode when Walt concedes that familial obligation was at best an illusion or an excuse, that his criminal life was mainly spurred by his own self-interest, and it&rsquo;s a realization that colors the show&rsquo;s brutal end.</p>', 'none', 'Every relationship in the show seems to have some familial basis.', 'none', 'Breaking Bad\nBryan Cranston\nCable television\nFamily\nVince Gilligan', 'xhtml', 'breaking-bad-family.jpg', 'none', '[145] [breaking-bad] Breaking Bad', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(148, 1, 2, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', NULL, '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', 'houseofcards2posterlarge.jpg', 'none', '2', 'none', '', 'none', 'Beau Willimon, based on the UK show created by Michael Dobbs and Andrew Davies', 'none', 'David Fincher, Kevin Spacey, Eric Roth, Joshua Donen, Dana Brunetti, Andrew Davies, Michael Dobbs, John Melfi, Beau Willimon, David Manson', 'none', 'Kevin Spacey\nRobin Wright', 'xhtml', 'Netflix', 'none', '81% (Season 1), 85% (Season 2)', 'none', '76% (Season 1), 80% (Season 2)', 'none', 'http://www.netflix.com/houseofcards', 'none', '<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/ULwUzF1q5w4" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'none', '<p>The US remake of the 1990s British political miniseries moves the shenanigans to Washington DC. After learning he won&#39;t be appointed to a coveted Cabinet position, House Majority Whip Francis Underwood (Kevin Spacey) and his wife Claire plan revenge on the administration he helped elect.</p>', 'none', '1', 'none', 'Beau Willimon\nDavid Fincher\nKevin Spacey\nNetflix\nPolitical thriller\nThe White House\nWashington, D.C.', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(149, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>Cranston made enormous contributions in&nbsp;developing his own character. Gilligan left a substantial amount of Walter&#39;s past unexplained so Cranston came up with his own backstory for the character. He even collaborated with costume designer Kathleen Detoro on a wardrobe of mostly neutral green and brown colors to make the character bland and unremarkable, and he worked with makeup artist Frieda Valenzuela to create a mustache he described as "impotent" and like a "dead caterpillar.&rdquo; <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/10/magazine/the-dark-art-of-breaking-bad.html">Cranston has said he was inspired partially by his elderly father</a> for how Walter carries himself physically, which he described as "a little hunched over, never erect, [as if] the weight of the world is on this man&#39;s shoulders.&rdquo;</p>', 'none', 'Cranston made enormous contributions in developing his own character.', 'none', 'AMC\nBreaking Bad\nBryan Cranston\nCable television', 'xhtml', 'Bryan-Cranston-Breaking-Bad033011.jpg', 'none', '[145] [breaking-bad] Breaking Bad', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(150, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>A few seasons into its run, the show hired Dr. Donna Nelson, a professor of organic chemistry at the University of Oklahoma, as an advisor after she approached the creators and offered her help. <a href="http://www.npr.org/2011/09/19/140111200/breaking-bad-vince-gilligan-on-meth-and-morals">According to Gilligan</a>, Nelson "vets our scripts to make sure our chemistry dialogue is accurate and up to date. We also have a chemist with the Drug Enforcement Administration based out of Dallas who has just been hugely helpful to us.&rdquo; In early episodes, a once common clandestine route, the Nagai red phosphorus/iodine method, is depicted, which uses pseudoephedrine as a precursor to d-(+)-methamphetamine. Later in the first season, Walt changes methods and is shown using a reductive amination reaction, relying on phenyl-2-propanone and methylamine. On the show the phenyl-2-propane, otherwise known as phenylacetone or P2P is produced from phenylacetic acid and acetic acid using a tube furnace and thorium dioxide or ThO2 as a catalyst. P2P and methylamine form an imine intermediate, and Walt can be seen creating a reduction of this P2P-methylamine imine intermediate using mercury aluminum amalgam.</p>', 'none', 'A few seasons into its run, the show hired Dr. Donna Nelson, a professor of organic chemistry at the University of Oklahoma, as an advisor.', 'none', 'AMC\nBreaking Bad\nCable television\nChemistry\nScience', 'xhtml', 'breaking_periodic_table.jpg', 'none', '[145] [breaking-bad] Breaking Bad', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(151, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>The image of a damaged pink teddy bear with a missing eye appears throughout the series. It first appears at the end of the music video "Fallacies" for Jesse&#39;s band "Twa&uuml;ghtHamm&euml;r.&rdquo; Later, it&rsquo;s seen on the mural on Jane&#39;s bedroom wall, in black &amp; white flash forwards where it is the only object in color, after a midair collision between to planes and in Walt&rsquo;s pool when the NTSB fishes it out.</p>\n\n<p><a href="http://cultural-learnings.com/2011/07/17/season-premiere-breaking-bad-box-cutter/">Television critic Myles McNutt has called it</a> "a reminder for Walt &ndash; a symbol of the damage he feels responsible for.&rdquo; But when Gilligan was asked about it, he said "the teddy bear eyeball that Walt found in his swimming pool is symbolic. It&#39;s very, very symbolic. However, I&#39;m not sure I can tell you with 100% certainty of what the symbolism is, what it represents...On the face of it, when we were coming up with that eye as an image, it probably, represented some form of the eye of the universe, the eye of god, the eye of morality, I suppose judging Walter White...And so symbolism like the eyeball, I&#39;m not sure what it means to me completely but I&#39;m always interested in hearing what it means to viewers of the show. I guess if you&#39;re going to hold my feet to the fire, what it means to me is the eye of God on Walt. If not necessarily judging him, nonetheless watching him, keeping tabs on him. And then the question: If that is what the symbolism stands for, then why does Walt keep that eye? Why does he keep it in his drawer versus discarding it?"</p>', 'none', 'The image of a damaged pink teddy bear with a missing eye appears throughout the series.', 'none', 'AMC\nBreaking Bad\nBryan Cranston\nCable television\nVince Gilligan', 'xhtml', 'PinkBear.jpg', 'none', '[145] [breaking-bad] Breaking Bad', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(152, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>The show explores government and Washington life in great, meticulous detail, and it&#39;s marked by cynicism towards the way government works, particularly those in power and how they wield their influence.</p>\n\n<p>It&rsquo;s worth noting that <em>House of Cards</em> was released at the time <em>Lincoln</em> hit theaters &ndash; that film was written as a governmental procedural, and screenwriter Tony Kushner admitted that the film reflected the current administration under Barack Obama. While <em>Lincoln</em> depicted the practical realities of government being bent towards idealistic motives, <em>House of Cards</em> had a polar opposite sensibility.</p>', 'none', 'It''s cynical towards the way government works, particularly those in power and how they wield their influence.', 'none', 'David Fincher\nNetflix\nPolitics\nThe White House\nWashington, D.C.', 'xhtml', 'hoc.jpg', 'none', '[148] [house-of-cards] House of Cards (U.S.)', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(153, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>The show&rsquo;s creators have always been conscious about basing many elements on the film on Shakespeare. <a href="http://www.salon.com/2014/02/14/yes_house_of_cards_is_our_shakespeare/">According to Robin Wright</a>, &ldquo;the way it was displayed to us, long before Episode 1 was ever written in Season 1, was you are Lady Macbeth to [Kevin Spacey]&#39;s Richard III.&rdquo;</p>\n\n<p><a href="http://www.salon.com/2014/02/14/yes_house_of_cards_is_our_shakespeare/">Daniel D&#39;Addario of Salon.com</a> asserts that &ldquo;viewed years from now, <em>House of Cards</em> may look like a history play about our era&rsquo;s utter disconnect between government and citizenry. Its flaws &mdash; the degree to which, for a show about politics, the politics themselves are pretty unreal &mdash; may indeed be assets in depicting the national level of confidence in government&hellip;the show gets at power by depicting not its effect on a nation but its effect on a single person. Perhaps, like Shakespeare, the writers of <em>House of Cards</em> have captured their times in a manner that future generations might study.&rdquo;</p>', 'none', '“The way it was displayed to us, long before Episode 1 was ever written in Season 1, was you are Lady Macbeth to his Richard III.”', 'none', 'Kevin Spacey\nNetflix\nPolitics\nThe White House\nWashington, D.C.', 'xhtml', '1600x1200.jpg', 'none', '[148] [house-of-cards] House of Cards (U.S.)', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(155, 1, 2, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', NULL, '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', 'true-detective-poster-art.jpg', 'none', '1', 'none', '8', 'none', 'Nic Pizzolatto', 'none', 'Richard Brown, Cary Fukunaga, Steve Golin, Woody Harrelson, Matthew McConaughey, Nic Pizzolatto, Scott Stephens', 'none', 'Matthew McConaughey\nWoody Harrelson\nMichelle Monaghan\nMichael Potts\nTory Kittles', 'xhtml', 'HBO', 'none', '85', 'none', '87', 'none', 'http://www.hbo.com/true-detective', 'none', '<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/TXwCoNwBSkQ" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'none', '<p>Multiple timelines trace a pair of homicide detectives in Louisiana - Martin Hart (Woody Harrelson) and his brooding, Texas-born partner, Rust Cohle (Matthew McConaughey) &ndash; investigating a serial killer across 17 years, from 1995 to 2012.</p>', 'none', '1', 'none', 'Antinatalism\nCable television\nComic books\nGothic Horror\nHBO\nPhilosophy\nSupernatural Horror', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(156, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p><a href="http://www.courier-journal.com/article/20100725/FEATURES06/307250014/Influences-Nic-Pizzolatto-novelist">Creator Nic Pizzolatto has said</a>, &ldquo;the first time I got excited about writing was reading comic books by Alan Moore and Grant Morrison as a kid. Growing up in southwest Louisiana, in a house without many books, the sophistication and depth of their stories were really mind-blowing for a kid.&rdquo;</p>\n\n<p><a href="http://blogs.indiewire.com/criticwire/the-comic-books-behind-true-detective">Many writers have noted parallels</a> between <em>True Detective</em> and Alan Moore and Eddie Campbell&#39;s comic book series on Jack the Ripper, <em>From Hell</em>. Both of them build similar, complex conspiracies around murder cases involving seemingly anonymous individuals. Even more striking are the similarities between the show and another comic by Alan Moore, <em>The Courtyard</em>, which features a detective who specializes in "anomaly theory,&rdquo; an investigative method that leads him to find connections between three crimes that initially have no apparent connection. The findings drive him mad, to the point where he actually performs the crimes he had been investigating.</p>\n\n<p>However, it&rsquo;s important to note that many of these comics were heavily influenced by other works of fiction, many of which Pizzolatto himself would later discover after his initial interest in comic books.</p>', 'none', 'Creator Nic Pizzolatto: "The first time I got excited about writing was reading comic books by Alan Moore and Grant Morrison as a kid."', 'none', 'Cable television\nComic books\nHBO\nTrue Detective', 'xhtml', 'k14lysr4msp2q5887mjy.jpg', 'none', '[155] [true-detective] True Detective', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(157, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>Many popular elements and themes from the supernatural horror genre can be seen in <em>True Detective</em>, and one can trace these back to specific sources in the direct references made to such works as Robert W. Chambers&#39; <u>The King in Yellow</u> (a collection of stories connected by a fictional, forbidden play that drives those who read it to insanity) and cult horror author Thomas Ligotti. <a href="http://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/01/30/the-most-shocking-thing-about-hbos-true-detective/">Many critics have also compared certain elements of the show to H.P. Lovecraft&rsquo;s stories</a>, though it should be noted that Chambers was very influential on Lovecraft and Lovecraft himself was fairly influential on Ligotti&rsquo;s work.</p>\n\n<p>Pizzolatto also cites horror authors Karl Edward Wagner, Laird Barron, John Langan, Simon Strantzas and the recent anthology <u>A Season in Carcosa</u> as being influential on his work. Outside of modern horror books, Pizzolatto also mentions <u>Confessions of an Antinatalist</u> by Jim Crawford, <u>Nihil Unbound</u> by Ray Brassier, <u>In The Dust of This Planet</u> by Eugene Thacker and <u>Better Never to Have Been</u> by David Benatar as being very influential on the philosophical overtones of the series.</p>', 'none', 'Many popular elements and themes from the supernatural horror genre can be seen in "True Detective."', 'none', 'Cable television\nH.P. Lovecraft\nHBO\nSupernatural horror\nTrue Detective', 'xhtml', '10-true-detective-1-1940x1091.jpg', 'none', '[155] [true-detective] True Detective', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(158, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>The show has often been described as &ldquo;antinatalist.&rdquo; Antinatalism is a philosophical position that assigns a negative value to birth, standing in opposition to natalism.</p>\n\n<p>As mentioned before, Pizzolatto was heavily influenced by Ligotti, he was known for antinatalist overtones in his often unsettling but darkly comic work. For example, in one of his more popular stories, &ldquo;The Conspiracy Against the Human Race,&rdquo; Ligotti describes human consciousness as &ldquo;the parent of all horrors.&rdquo; Much of Detective Cohle&rsquo;s dialogue seems directly pulled from Ligotti&rsquo;s writing.</p>\n\n<p>At one point, Cohle says, &ldquo;We became too self aware; nature created an aspect of nature separate from itself. We are creatures that should not exist by natural law. We are things that labor under the illusion of having a self, a secretion of sensory experience and feeling, programmed with total assurance that we are each somebody, when in fact everybody&rsquo;s nobody. I think the honorable thing for our species to do is deny our programming, stop reproducing, walk hand in hand into extinction, one last midnight, brothers and sisters opting out of a raw deal. &ldquo;</p>\n\n<p>In &ldquo;The Conspiracy Against the Human Race,&rdquo; where Ligotti writes: &ldquo;Now we know that we are uncanny paradoxes. We know that nature has veered into the supernatural by fabricating a creature that cannot and should not exist by natural law, and yet does. &ldquo;</p>\n\n<p>And other passages from that book: &ldquo;The worst possible thing we could know &mdash; worse than knowing of our descent from a mass of microorganisms &mdash; is that we are nobodies not somebodies, puppets not people.&rdquo;</p>\n\n<p>&ldquo;For us, then, life is a confidence trick we must run on ourselves, hoping we do not catch on to any monkey business that would leave us stripped of our defense mechanisms and standing stark naked before the silent, staring void. To end this self-deception, to free our species of the paradoxical imperative to be and not to be conscious, our backs breaking by degrees upon a wheel of lies, we must cease reproducing.&rdquo;</p>\n\n<p>Though Pizzolatto has been open about his influences, he claims his show doesn&rsquo;t necessarily share the philosophy of those works, even though he draws his material from them. &ldquo;I wouldn&rsquo;t want any viewers to assume we had some nihilistic agenda, or reduce Cohle to an anti-natalist or nihilist. Cohle is more complicated than that. As I&rsquo;ve said recently, Cohle may claim to be a nihilist, but an observation of him reveals otherwise. Far from &lsquo;nothing meaning anything&rsquo; to him, it&rsquo;s almost as though everything means too much to him. He&rsquo;s too passionate, too acutely sensitive, and he cares too much to be labeled a successful nihilist. And in his monologues, don&rsquo;t we detect a whiff of desperation akin to someone who protests too much? When Cohle speaks of the unspeakable, is it with the same illusory perspective as when Hart speaks about the importance of having rules and boundaries?&rdquo;</p>', 'none', 'The show has often been described as “antinatalist.”', 'none', 'Antinatalist\nCable television\nHBO\nTrue Detective', 'xhtml', 'o-TRUE-DETECTIVE-facebook.jpg', 'none', '[155] [true-detective] True Detective', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(159, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>&ldquo;Whatever story you&rsquo;re telling in Louisiana, the landscape is going to become a character in it,&rdquo; says Pizzolatto. &ldquo;I grew up in Louisiana and spent my formative years there. There&rsquo;s a contradictory nature to the place and a sort of sinister quality underneath it all. Everything lives under layers of concealment. The woods are thick and dark and impenetrable. On the other hand you have the beauty of it all from a distance. One Southern writer who&rsquo;s meant a lot to me is William Faulkner. His understanding of the South and its paradoxes is one of the most comprehensive and legitimate artistic portraits of the South that exists. That&rsquo;s something I&rsquo;ve tapped into a lot: the dissonances of contradiction. In the South the sacred and the profane exist hand-in-hand.&rdquo;</p>', 'none', '“Whatever story you’re telling in Louisiana, the landscape is going to become a character in it,” says show creator Nic Pizzolatto.', 'none', 'Cable television\nHBO\nLocations\nLouisiana\nNew Orleans\nTrue Detective', 'xhtml', '1-church.jpg', 'none', '[155] [true-detective] True Detective', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(160, 1, 2, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'game-of-thrones-tv-movie-poster-2011-1010697745.jpg', 'none', '4', 'none', '40', 'none', 'David Benioff, D. B. Weiss', 'none', 'David Benioff, D. B. Weiss, Frank Doelger, Bernadette Caulfield, Carolyn Strauss, George R. R. Martin', 'none', 'Lena Headey\nPeter Dinklage\nEmilia Clarke\nMaisie Williams', 'xhtml', 'HBO', 'none', '83% (Season 1), 97% (Season 2), 100% (Season 3), 96% (Season 4)', 'none', '79% (Season 1), 88% (Season 2), 90% (Season 3), 94% (Season 4)', 'none', 'http://www.hbo.com/game-of-thrones', 'none', '<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/YinJaXzgzqI" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'none', '<p>The series is based on George R.R. Martin&#39;s novel about a fantasy world where royal houses battle for the Iron Throne.</p>', 'none', '1', 'none', 'Cable television\nGeorge R. R. Martin\nHBO\nMedieval\nWar', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(161, 1, 2, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'downton_abbey.jpg', 'none', '5', 'none', '43', 'none', 'Julian Fellowes', 'none', 'Julian Fellowes, Gareth Neame, Rebecca Eaton', 'none', 'Hugh Bonneville\nElizabeth McGovern\nMichelle Dockery\nLaura Carmichael\nJessica Brown Findlay\nMaggie Smith\nAllen Leech\nDan Stevens\nPenelope Wilton\nSamantha Bond', 'xhtml', 'ITV, STV, UTV', 'none', '93% (Season 1), 100% (Season 2), 78% (Season 3), 69% (Season 4), 79% (Season 5)', 'none', '91% (Season 1), 84% (Season 2), 83% (Season 3), 72% (Season 4), 75% (Season 5)', 'none', 'http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/masterpiece/downtonabbey/', 'none', '<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/EOM3y4P8TEM" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'none', '<p>Set in the fictional&nbsp;Lord Robert Grantham&#39;s&nbsp;Yorkshire&nbsp;country estate&nbsp;of Downton Abbey, the British mini-series&nbsp;depicts the lives of the&nbsp;aristocratic Crawley family and their servants in the post-Edwardian era&mdash;with the great events in history having an effect on their lives and on the British social hierarchy. Such events depicted throughout the series include news of the&nbsp;sinking of the RMS&nbsp;Titanic&nbsp;in the first series; the outbreak of the&nbsp;First World War, the&nbsp;Spanish influenza pandemic, and the&nbsp;Marconi scandal&nbsp;in the second series; the&nbsp;interwar period&nbsp;and the formation of the&nbsp;Irish Free State&nbsp;in the third series; the&nbsp;Teapot Dome scandal&nbsp;in the fourth series; and the&nbsp;United Kingdom general election of 1923&nbsp;and the&nbsp;Beer Hall Putsch&nbsp;in the fifth series.</p>', 'none', '1', 'none', 'British television\nHistorical drama\nPBS\nPeriod pieces\nPolitics\nSocial conservatism', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(164, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>Some have criticized the show&#39;s portrayal of Irish history through it&#39;s Irish characters, <a href="http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/around-town/downtons-not-antiirish-says-star-alan-28851689.html">particularly by the Irish newspaper The Herald</a>. For example, the character Tom Branson&#39;s brother Kieran has been compared to a drunken, uncouth Irish stereotype. Furthermore, Robert Crawley&#39;s anti-Catholic views has drawn <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/she-the-people/wp/2013/01/29/the-politics-of-downton-abbey-down-with-the-patriarchy/">some accusations of xenophobia</a>.</p>\n\n<p>But some, like <a href="http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/around-town/downtons-not-antiirish-says-star-alan-28851689.html">Dublin-born&nbsp;<em>Downton Abbey</em>&nbsp;actor&nbsp;Allen Leech</a>, disagree, with Leech arguing that&nbsp;the anti-Irish sentiments of the show are meant to reflect the racist attitudes of the time.&nbsp;<a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/downton-abbey/9624196/Downton-Abbeys-anti-Catholic-plot.html">Show creator Julian Fellowes, a Catholic himself, chose to&nbsp;depict&nbsp;anti-Catholicism in the upper-class because it was&nbsp;a common observation he remembers from his childhood.</a></p>', 'none', 'Some have criticized the show''s portrayal of Irish history through it''s Irish characters.', 'none', 'British politics\nBritish television\nRacism\nXenophobia', 'xhtml', 'Downton_Abbey_Video_1380x715.jpg', 'none', '[161] [downton-abbey] Downton Abbey', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(162, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p><em>Game of Thrones</em> has been called one of the most graphic shows on television, and this had led to criticism for its frequent sex and nudity, often focused on women, sometimes with very graphic violence. Some critics have called much of this gratuitous, to the point of soft pornography. <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/01/14/game-of-thrones-stephen-dillane-the-tunnel_n_4595628.html">Even cast member Stephen Dillane compared the show to "German porn from the 1970s."</a> The controversy has continued to grow, with many pointing out that the nudity isn&rsquo;t even historically accurate (given the grooming habits of the characters involved) and that some scenes in recent episodes even deviate from their source material in a violent and demeaning way for the women involved. <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/may/06/george-rr-martin-game-of-thrones-sexual-violence">George R. R. Martin has defended the show</a>, arguing that such scenes were crucial to the stories because they showed how &ldquo;the true horrors of human history derive&hellip;from ourselves.&rdquo;</p>', 'none', '"Game of Thrones" has been called one of the most graphic shows on television, and this had led to criticism for its frequent sex and nudity, often focused on women, sometimes with very graphic violence.', 'none', 'Cable television\nGame of Thrones\nGender studies\nHBO\nMisogyny\nSex', 'xhtml', 'misogyny.jpg', 'none', '[160] [game-of-thrones] Game of Thrones', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(163, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>A lot of writers, noting creator Julian Fellowes&rsquo; lifelong monarchist Tory politics, have argued that the show is the most conservative drama on television. <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/emma-brockes-blog/2014/feb/06/downton-abbey-conservative-politics">Emma Brockes of The Guardian notes that</a> &ldquo;Tom the chauffeur had his Irish nationalist phase, which one understands to have been rather silly of him. The show favors a brand of Conservative paternalism embodied by Lord Grantham, who is a good man, and Mary, who, let&#39;s face it, is a proto-Thatcherite.&rdquo; <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2011/dec/18/julian-fellowes-faces-2011-downton">Fellowes himself told the Guardian</a>, &rdquo;At the risk of sounding sentimental, I believe the monarchy stands for a fairness that we like to think represents us. I hope &lsquo;Downton&rsquo; has that kind of decency about it.&rdquo;</p>\n\n<p>Yet many of the same critics note that a large portion of its audience has identified itself with liberal. Though there&rsquo;s no simple explanation connecting the show&rsquo;s politics to its appeal, some have attempted to rationalize this discrepancy. For example, the show spend as much time on the servants as the upper-class family, and according to <a href="http://www.salon.com/2012/01/07/why_liberals_love_downton_abbey/">Bruce Covert, editor of the Roosevelt Institute&rsquo;s New Deal 2.0 blog</a>, &ldquo;the rigid class structure is clearly oppressive for everyone involved. It&rsquo;s not just the servants who suffer from it, but Lady Mary, Matthew and everyone caught up in the entail.&rdquo;</p>', 'none', 'A lot of writers, noting creator Julian Fellowes’ lifelong monarchist Tory politics, have argued that the show is the most conservative drama on television.', 'none', 'British politics\nBritish television\nConservatism\nPolitics', 'xhtml', 'downton-abbey-servants.jpg', 'none', '[161] [downton-abbey] Downton Abbey', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none');
