(167, 1, 2, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'homeland-sezonul-1-season-1-poster.jpg', 'none', '4', 'none', '48', 'none', 'Howard Gordon & Alex Gansa based on "Prisoners of War" by Gideon Raff', 'none', 'Avi Nir, Ran Telem, Gideon Raff, Michael Cuesta, Howard Gordon, Alex Gansa, Henry Bromell, Alexander Cary, Chip Johannessen, Meredith Stiehm', 'none', 'Claire Danes\nDamian Lewis\nMorena Baccarin\nDavid Harewood\nDiego Klattenhoff\nJackson Pace\nMorgan Saylor\nMandy Patinkin\nJamey Sheridan\nDavid Marciano\nNavid Negahban\nRupert Friend\nSarita Choudhury\nTracy Letts\nF. Murray Abraham\nNazanin Boniadi', 'xhtml', 'Showtime', 'none', '100% (Season 1), 97% (Season 2), 84% (Season 3), 90% (Season 4)', 'none', '91% (Season 1), 96% (Season 2), 77% (Season 3) 74% (Season 4)', 'none', 'http://www.sho.com/sho/homeland/home', 'none', '<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/KyFmS3wRPCQ" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'none', '<p>CIA agent Carrie Mathison (Claire Danes) is not convinced the rescued soldier Nick Brody (Damian Lewis) is not a double agent of al-Qaida.</p>', 'none', '1', 'none', 'Espionage\nPolitical thriller\nPolitics\nTerrorism\nTorture\nWar\nWashington, D.C.', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(166, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>Despite efforts at period detail, the show has been criticized widely for its linguistic anachronisms, including the contemporary accents of the wealthy characters. <a href="http://www.newsweek.com/why-americans-have-fallen-snobby-downton-abbey-64157">Some historians like Simon Schama have also been critical of the show&#39;s historical inaccuracies</a>. The relationships between the upper class and the servants have been called too informal by some (for example, servants below the level of butler and housekeeper regularly ignore protocol and address senior members of the family with personal requests or observations), but often times this has been defended as a dramatic license.</p>', 'none', 'Despite efforts at period detail, the show has been criticized widely for its linguistic anachronisms.', 'none', 'British television\nHistorical accuracy', 'xhtml', 'downton_abbey_christmas_2013__131110163527.jpg', 'none', '[161] [downton-abbey] Downton Abbey', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(168, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>Frankenheimer&rsquo;s landmark film also deals with a prisoner of war who returns home as a war hero even though he&rsquo;s secretly switched his allegiance to another country. Besides the premise, many critics have noted that both works portray a symbiotic relationship between the United States and its enemies. In Frankenheimer&rsquo;s darkly satirical film, breeding fears of Communism fuels a plot to bring authoritarian rule to the U.S. led by a covert Communist agent; in <em>Homeland</em>,&nbsp;U.S. foreign policy addressing terrorism winds up breeding anti-American sentiment that leads to a growth in terrorist recruits.</p>', 'none', 'Frankenheimer’s landmark film also deals with a similar premise.', 'none', 'Cable television\nPolitics\nShowtime\nTerrorism\nThe Cold War', 'xhtml', 'manchurian-mama.png', 'none', '[167] [homeland] Homeland', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(169, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>The show has been criticized by some for its portrayal of Muslims, particularly <a href="http://www.salon.com/2012/12/15/tvs_most_islamophobic_show/">Al Jazeera broadcast journalist Laila Al-Arian</a>, who wrote a widely-read, scathing review for Salon, and <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/oct/13/homeland-drama-offensive-portrayal-islam-arabs">foreign affairs editor Peter Beaumont of The Guardian</a>, who wrote that &ldquo;it does not matter whether [the Arabs and Muslims] are rich, smart, discreetly enjoying a western lifestyle or attractive: all are to be suspected.&rdquo; Beaumont also criticized the way the show portrayed the political realities of the Middle East, writing that &ldquo;there is more to it than the portrayal of individuals. For <em>Homeland</em> presents an odd and unbelievable image of relationships between countries and identities in the region, where Palestinians, Iraqis, Saudis all share an agenda regardless of background, culture and history.&rdquo; However, the subject remains fiercely debated, with many other writers like <a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2012/12/homeland-is-anything-but-islamophobic/266418/">Yair Rosenberg for The Atlantic</a> and <a href="http://tabletmag.com/scroll/119607/homeland-is-obviously-anti-semitic">The Tablet&#39;s Zach Novetsky</a> arguing that those criticizing the show&rsquo;s politics are misinterpreting what&rsquo;s actually being shown.</p>', 'none', 'There has been debate over the show''s depiction of the political realities of the Middle East.', 'none', 'Politics\nThe Middle East', 'xhtml', 'Homeland-theres-something-else-going-on-5.jpg', 'none', '[167] [homeland] Homeland', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(171, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>Even though <em>Girls</em> wasn&rsquo;t thematically an enormous departure from Dunham&rsquo;s previous work, it was her first work to be widely distributed for a broad, mainstream audience, and it was met with enormous controversy before it even aired. Much of it revolved around its feminist politics, and critics were polarized. <a href="http://www.motherjones.com/mixed-media/2012/04/counterpoint-girls-HBO-lena-dunham">Some praised it for its depiction of women and their relationships</a>, as it was a rare high-profile television show that made the female image, abortion and modern sexual behavior among young women part of its basic fabric. However, others felt its explorations of such topics were <a href="http://gawker.com/5902308/small-girl-big-mouth-a-girls-recap">narcissistic</a> or possibly <a href="http://thehairpin.com/2012/04/where-my-girls-at">undermined by their seeming exclusion of other classes and races</a>.</p>', 'none', 'Some praised it for its depiction of women and their relationships, others felt it was narcissistic and undermined by its seeming exclusion of other classes and races.', 'none', 'Cable television\nFeminism\nHBO', 'xhtml', 'hbo-s-girls-is-the-best-new-tv-show-of-2012.jpg', 'none', '[170] [girls] Girls', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(172, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>The most concrete example of influence on the show has to do with the criticism over race. As mentioned, race was one of the first subjects raised with <em>Girls</em>, and even though the show had plenty of defenders (many of whom felt that the show was being unfairly singled out), Dunham conceded that she was very sensitive about that point. <a href="http://www.npr.org/2012/05/07/152183865/lena-dunham-addresses-criticism-aimed-at-girls">She told NPR</a>, &ldquo;I wrote the first season primarily by myself, and I co-wrote a few episodes. But I am a half-Jew, half-WASP, and I wrote two Jews and two WASPs. Something I wanted to avoid was tokenism in casting. If I had one of the four girls, if, for example, she was African-American, I feel like &mdash; not that the experience of an African-American girl and a white girl are drastically different, but there has to be specificity to that experience [that] I wasn&#39;t able to speak to. I really wrote the show from a gut-level place, and each character was a piece of me or based on someone close to me. And only later did I realize that it was four white girls. As much as I can say it was an accident, it was only later as the criticism came out, I thought, &#39;I hear this and I want to respond to it.&#39; And this is a hard issue to speak to because all I want to do is sound sensitive and not say anything that will horrify anyone or make them feel more isolated, but I did write something that was super-specific to my experience, and I always want to avoid rendering an experience I can&#39;t speak to accurately.&rdquo; As a result of the criticism, she wrote in minorities into the show, developing them around her concerns and consciously trying to avoid stereotypes associated with particular ethnicities.</p>', 'none', 'Some complained about its seeming exclusion of other classes and races.', 'none', 'Cable television\nHBO\nRace', 'xhtml', 'girls14_68.jpg', 'none', '[170] [girls] Girls', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(170, 1, 2, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Girls_HBO_Poster.jpg', 'none', '4', 'none', '37', 'none', 'Lena Dunham', 'none', 'Lena Dunham, Judd Apatow, Jennifer Konner, Ilene S. Landress, Bruce Eric Kaplan', 'none', 'Lena Dunham\nAllison Williams\nJemima Kirke\nZosia Mamet\nAdam Driver\nAlex Karpovsky\nAndrew Rannells', 'xhtml', 'HBO', 'none', '95% (Season 1),  94% (Season 2),  89% (Season 3)', 'none', '87% (Season 1),  84% (Season 2),  76% (Season 3)', 'none', 'http://www.hbo.com/girls/index.html', 'none', '<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/oMK8PbjPwhA" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'none', '<p>Hannah, Jessa, Marnie, and Shoshanna are four 20-something girls living in New York and trying to figure out life, love, and themselves in the HBO series created by Lena Dunham.</p>', 'none', '1', 'none', 'Cable television\nFeminism\nHBO', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(173, 1, 2, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'louie.jpg', 'none', '5', 'none', '60', 'none', 'Louis C.K.', 'none', 'Louis C.K., Dave Becky, M. Blair Breard', 'none', 'Louis C.K.', 'xhtml', 'FX', 'none', '86% (Season 1), 100% (Season 2),  100% (Season 3),  92% (Season 4)', 'none', '70% (Season 1),  90% (Season 2),  94% (Season 3),  93% (Season 4)', 'none', 'http://www.fxnetworks.com/louie/', 'none', '<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/FkvtunT5Xh4" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'none', '<p>Stand-up comedian Louie C.K. draws from his own life as a divorced single father in this new comedy for FX.</p>', 'none', '1', 'none', 'Aging\nCable television\nDark comedy\nFX\nMature comedy\nSingle parenthood\nStand-up comedians', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(175, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p><a href="http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/louis-ck-tour-tickets-louie-season-3-342590">According to Louie C.K.</a>, &ldquo;When I was drawing from my own life, I didn&#39;t want to have the story be about an ex-husband and ex-wife -- that relationship wasn&#39;t what I wanted to write about. I arrived at a version of it for this character that I thought was good, this woman who&#39;s well put-together and an added pressure to his life. And the actress (Susan Kelechi Watson)&nbsp;was so good. A lot of the stuff that we do on the show, I&#39;m not sure I&#39;m going to do it until I see who&#39;s playing it. It&#39;s part of having the freedom without a network where you have to run all the scripts and casting by people. I wrote the script with her in it and I had the casting people go look for someone, and I told them open it way up and just bring anybody. And I really liked what this woman did, so I decided to stick with the character.&rdquo;</p>', 'none', '"I arrived at a version of it for this character that I thought was good, this woman who''s well put-together and an added pressure to his life."', 'none', 'Cable television\nFX', 'xhtml', 'Susan_Kelechi_Watson.png', 'none', '[173] [louie] Louie', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(176, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>No. While the premise (like much of his stand-up comedy) draws heavily from his own personal life, it was merely a starting point. <a href="http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/louis-ck-tour-tickets-louie-season-3-342590">As Louie C.K. has stated many times</a>, &ldquo;the show has broken off into fiction much more in the last year and this year, so it&#39;s really not drawing from my life anymore.&rdquo;</p>', 'none', 'While the premise (like much of his stand-up comedy) draws heavily from his own personal life, it was merely a starting point.', 'none', 'Cable television\nFX\nStand-up comedians', 'xhtml', 'jsGAD.png', 'none', '[173] [louie] Louie', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(174, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>Though the show does maintain certain elements from episode-to-episode, Louie C. K. made it clear that he&rsquo;s not dedicated to continuity and more than willing to break from television conventions in order to experiment with new ideas. Even basic facts about Louie&rsquo;s life -&nbsp;like details about his wife, how many&nbsp;siblings has has and his&nbsp;mother&#39;s personality&nbsp;-&nbsp;will change from one episode to another.&nbsp;As he&rsquo;s told numerous interviewers, &ldquo;The show needs to keep going, so I&#39;m introducing new elements each year.&rdquo; So while there are some ideas and stories that are developed over multiple episodes, there are also numerous single episodes that are written with little regard for past episodes.</p>', 'none', 'Louie C. K. made it clear that he’s not dedicated to continuity.', 'none', 'Cable television\nFX', 'xhtml', 'lck.jpg', 'none', '[173] [louie] Louie', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(177, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>The fourth season featured an episode where Louie tries to rape a friend and recurring character who had been the object of infatuation in prior seasons. (It&rsquo;s one of a handful of core plot elements that Louie has maintained through most of the show&rsquo;s run.) Up to that point, some writers had championed the show for its attempts at interesting and original (albeit eccentric) portrayals of female characters. <a href="http://www.styleite.com/features/opinion/louies-rape-scene-just-destroyed-his-feminist-agenda/">As one commentator, Ashley Hoffman, noted</a>, &ldquo;[Pamela] was a refreshing change to the caricatured female love interest, and then [Louie] made her powerless when he grabbed at her.&rdquo; However, <a href="http://www.salon.com/2014/06/03/this_would_be_rape_if_you_werent_so_stupid_louies_most_disturbing_scene_yet/">Neil Drumming of Salon.com</a> argued that the scene was far more complex than its critics realized. &ldquo;This is hardly the first time this season that Louis C.K. has directly referenced the issue of violence against women. In an early episode, he was, once again, the perpetrator of such violence, albeit by accident&hellip;Louis C.K.&rsquo;s willingness to acknowledge injustice and inequality, however discomfiting in its expression, has earned him a great deal of credit and esteem as a creator. His eagerness to implicate himself in it &mdash; Louie the character, Louis the auteur &mdash; has created the complicated portrait of a man who requires a public forum in which to struggle with his darkest impulses.&rdquo;</p>', 'none', 'The fourth season featured an episode where Louie tries to rape a friend and recurring character who had been the object of infatuation in prior seasons.', 'none', 'Cable television\nFeminism\nFX', 'xhtml', 'Screen-Shot-2014-06-05-at-09.38.23-e1401954545248.png', 'none', '[173] [louie] Louie', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(179, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>A lot of research actually goes into show, with much of the setting based on the actual workings of real life, local governments. For example, the dynamics of the town hall scenes were heavily shaped by actual community hearings attended by the writers. Even real life government officials are often used as consultants for the series, most notably California city planner Mark Scott Albright, who consulted for the show in their development of Mark Brendanawicz. Even Ron Swanson reportedly came out of a chance meeting with a Libertarian who was serving in a local office.</p>\n\n<p>In terms of the actual storylines, many have been shaped by real-life events. Season-length story arcs often were inspired by larger news stories like the government shutdown and the financial meltdown, which individual events often took inspiration by smaller news stories like the controversial arrest of Harvard professor Henry Louis Gates.</p>', 'none', 'A lot of research actually goes into show, with much of the setting based on the actual workings of real life, local governments.', 'none', 'NBC\npolitical satire\npolitics\nsingle camera sitcoms', 'xhtml', 'biden_parks_and_recreation-copy.jpg', 'none', '[178] [parks-and-recreation] Parks and Recreation', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(180, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>Show runner Michael Schur has stated that the show is &ldquo;certainly not apolitical," which a lead character who &ldquo;believes that government can do good things, and that&rsquo;s generally speaking, a Democratic idea." Besides Amy Poehler&rsquo;s character, the show is also shaped by the kind of humor and character dynamics favored by Schur, elements that may actually have apolitical motives even though the result does have an impact on how the show portrays government. Schur says that he and the writing staff made a conscious decision not to build the show around the same kind of cynical perspective that he felt was defining most television shows currently on the air. "I&#39;ve never liked mean-spirited comedy. The characters on our show make fun of each other, but not in a biting, angry way. And there&#39;s no shortage of conflict in the world of government.&rdquo;</p>', 'none', 'Show runner Michael Schur has stated that the show is “certainly not apolitical."', 'none', 'NBC\npolitical satire\npolitics\nsingle camera sitcoms', 'xhtml', 'nup_151090_0004.jpg', 'none', '[178] [parks-and-recreation] Parks and Recreation', 'none', 'Screen Prism', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
