(192, 1, 1, 'breathless_french_poster1960.jpg', 'none', 'Jean-Luc Godard', 'none', '1', 'none', 'Jean-Paul Belmondo\nJean Seberg', 'xhtml', '<p>There was before&nbsp;<em>Breathless</em>,&nbsp;and there was after&nbsp;<em>Breathless</em>.&nbsp;Jean-Luc Godard burst onto the film scene in 1960 with this jazzy, free-form, and sexy homage to the American film genres that inspired him as a writer for&nbsp;<em>Cahiers du cin&eacute;ma</em>.&nbsp;With its lack of polish, surplus of attitude, anything-goes crime narrative, and effervescent young stars Jean-Paul Belmondo and Jean Seberg,&nbsp;<em>Breathless</em>&nbsp;helped launch the French New Wave and ensured that cinema would never be the same.</p>', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Jean-Luc Godard', 'none', '', NULL, 'French New Wave\nJean-Luc Godard\nModern cinema\nWorld cinema', 'xhtml', 'Georges de Beauregard', 'none', 'UGC', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', 'http://www.criterion.com/films/268-breathless', 'none', '<iframe width="420" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/WCDEAu4R8hA" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(194, 1, 1, 'raging_bull.jpg', 'none', 'Martin Scorsese', 'none', '1', 'none', 'Robert DeNiro\nCathy Moriarty\nJoe Pesci\nNicholas Colasanto\nFrank Vincent', 'xhtml', '<p>Jake LaMotta is an Italian American middleweight boxer whose self-destructive and obsessive rage, sexual jealousy, and animalistic appetite destroys his relationship with his wife and family.</p>', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Paul Schrader, Mardik Martin', 'none', '', NULL, 'Biopics\nBoxing\nDomestic violence\nMartin Scorsese\nMethod acting\nMisogyny\nNew Hollywood\nRobert DeNiro\nSports movies\nViolence', 'xhtml', 'Robert Chartoff, Irwin Winkler', 'none', 'United Artists', 'none', '$18 million', 'none', '$23,380,203', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '98%', 'none', '92%', 'none', '', 'none', '<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/yUp6d79WRVI" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(196, 1, 1, 'amanecer.jpg', 'none', 'F. W. Murnau', 'none', '1', 'none', 'George O''Brien\n Janet Gaynor\nMargaret Livingston', 'xhtml', '<p>The culmination of one of the greatest careers in film history, F. W. Murnau&rsquo;s&nbsp;<em>Sunrise</em>&nbsp;blends a story of fable-like simplicity with unparalleled visual imagination and technical ingenuity. Invited to Hollywood by William Fox and given total artistic freedom on any project he wished, Murnau&rsquo;s tale of the idyllic marriage of a peasant couple (George O&rsquo;Brien and Janet Gaynor) threatened by a Machiavellian seductress from the city (Margaret Livingston) created a milestone of film expressionism.</p>\n\n<p>Made in the twilight of the silent era, it became both a swan song for a vanishing medium and one of the few films to instantly achieve legendary status. Winner of three Oscars for Best Actress (Gaynor), Cinematography, and a never-repeated award for &ldquo;Unique and Artistic Picture&rdquo;, its influence and stature has only grown with each passing year.</p>', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Carl Mayer based on "Die Reise nach Tilsit" by Hermann Sudermann', 'none', '', NULL, '', 'xhtml', 'William Fox', 'none', 'Fox Film Corporation', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', 'https://www.eurekavideo.co.uk/moc/sunrise', 'none', '<iframe width="420" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/jGZF1_pfErs" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(197, 1, 1, 'Tokyo_Story_poster.jpg', 'none', 'Yasujirō Ozu', 'none', '1', 'none', 'Chishū Ryū\nChieko Higashiyama\nSetsuko Hara', 'xhtml', '<p>A profoundly stirring evocation of elemental humanity and universal heartbreak,<em>&nbsp;Tokyo Story</em>&nbsp;is the crowning achievement of the unparalleled Yasujiro Ozu. The film, which follows an aging couple&rsquo;s journey to visit their grown children in bustling postwar Tokyo, surveys the rich and complex world of family life with the director&rsquo;s customary delicacy and incisive perspective on social mores. Featuring lovely performances from Ozu regulars Chishu Ryu and Setsuko Hara,&nbsp;<em>Tokyo Story</em>&nbsp;plumbs and deepens the director&rsquo;s recurring theme of generational conflict, creating what is without question one of cinema&rsquo;s mightiest masterpieces.</p>', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Kōgo Noda, Yasujirō Ozu', 'none', '', NULL, 'Domestic drama\nJapanese cinema\nMinimalism\nWorld cinema\nYasujirō Ozu', 'xhtml', 'Takeshi Yamamoto', 'none', 'Shochiku', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', 'http://www.criterion.com/films/284-tokyo-story', 'none', '<iframe width="420" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/1GYdSLN1rzk" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(198, 1, 1, 'rules-of-the-game-movie-poster-1939-1020421065.jpg', 'none', 'Jean Renoir', 'none', '1', 'none', 'Nora Gregor\nPaulette Dubost\nMila Parély\nMarcel Dalio\nJulien Carette\nRoland Toutain\nGaston Modot\nPierre Magnier\nJean Renoir', 'xhtml', '<p>Considered one of the greatest films ever made,&nbsp;<em>The Rules of the Game</em>&nbsp;(<em>La r&egrave;gle du jeu</em>), by Jean Renoir, is a scathing critique of corrupt French society cloaked in a comedy of manners in which a weekend at a marquis&rsquo; country ch&acirc;teau lays bare some ugly truths about a group of haut bourgeois acquaintances.</p>', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Jean Renoir, Carl Koch', 'none', '', NULL, 'French cinema\nJean Renoir\nWorld cinema', 'xhtml', 'Claude Renoir, Jean Jay', 'none', 'The Gaumont Film Company', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', 'http://www.criterion.com/films/295-the-rules-of-the-game', 'none', '<iframe width="420" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/qxs4P6u1EiI" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none'),
(200, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '<p>When Stanley Kubrick was adapting the Peter George novel&nbsp;Red Alert, the&nbsp;rationale&nbsp;behind&nbsp;nuclear warfare&nbsp;couldn&#39;t help but seem ridiculous, and it&#39;s a stroke of genius that Kubrick not only transformed the material into the black comedy, <em>Dr. Strangelove</em>,&nbsp;but found a perfect representation&nbsp;for&nbsp;the insanity in the sexual imagery running throughout the film.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>The opening image of a bomber refueling as "Try a Little Tenderness" brazenly plays over the soundtrack&nbsp;has been compared to copulation, and Dr. Strangelove&rsquo;s rise from his wheelchair, immediately preceding a montage of mushroom clouds, as well as Slim Pickens&rsquo; iconic ride on the bomb, have also been compared to sexual climax. Many of the names have sexual overtones, and there&#39;s rarely a moment where their activities or thought process isn&#39;t sexualized in some way.</p>\n\n<p>General Jack D. Ripper starts the bombing campaign against the Soviets after a moment of impotence leads him a&nbsp;paranoid obsession with "bodily fluids." General Buck Turgidson is in the middle of a tryst with his secretary when he gets a phone call about the attack. Premier Dmitiri Kissof&nbsp;is off doing the same when they&#39;re having a hard time tracking him down.&nbsp;Female genitalia is referenced in both the first and last names of the President of the United States. And when they go over the details of surviving in a world&nbsp;post-nuclear annihilation, one of the key elements is providing as many women as possible for each male survivor.</p>\n\n<p>These allusions undermine any potential solemnness of the plot, tying most of the action to base primal motivations rather than any pure intellectual reasoning. War comes off as&nbsp;a surrogate for male sexual frustration.</p>', 'none', ' Some argue that the film suggests war as a surrogate for male sexual frustration.', 'none', 'Sex\nStanley Kubrick\nThe Cold War\nWar', 'xhtml', 'dr_strangelove.jpg', 'none', '[185] [dr.-strangelove-or-how-i-learned-to-stop-worrying-and-love-the-bomb] Dr. Strangelove or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb', 'none', '[208] [wu-mitchell] Mitchell Wu', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none');
