(209, 1, 145, 36, NULL, 0, 6, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Vince Gilligan shares 5 alternate endings to "Breaking Bad"', 'No. 1: Walter White goes Rambo...', 'The Wrap', 'http://www.thewrap.com/breaking-bad-vince-gilligan-shares-5-alternate-endings/'),
(213, 1, 114, 3, NULL, 0, 6, 'The hard work of marriage', 'Zoë Heller, The New York Review of Books', 'http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2014/dec/04/gone-girl-hard-work-marriage/', 'The belief that conjugal happiness can be earned only by rigorous and sustained emotional labor is so deeply entrenched in the common culture that when Amy Dunne boasts cheerfully of finding marriage “easy,” it is as if she had entered Dracula’s castle scoffing at the existence of vampires: the audience knows at once that her hubris must be punished.\n', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(214, 1, 6, 3, NULL, 0, 6, 'A nightmare on Broadway', 'Francine Prose, The New York Review of Books', 'http://www.nybooks.com/blogs/nyrblog/2015/jan/28/birdman-nightmare-broadway/', 'Alejandro González Iñárritu has taken his cinematic nightmare to the Great White Way, illuminated it with Broadway footlights, located the pathos—and the hilarity—in the New York stage, and given us a cast of nuanced and beautifully acted minor characters.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(215, 1, 102, 3, NULL, 0, 11, 'Denouncing surveillance, on camera', 'David Cole, The New York Review of Books', 'http://www.nybooks.com/blogs/nyrblog/2014/oct/25/citizenfour-denouncing-surveillance/', 'In their extraordinary revelations about what the NSA and its secret programs have been doing, Edward Snowden’s leaks have shown the precariousness of privacy in the digital age. But Laura Poitras’ film also demonstrates, unwittingly, that we are part of the problem. We have chosen to broadcast our lives.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(216, 1, 102, 3, NULL, 0, 12, 'The question of Edward Snowden', 'David Bromwich, The New York Review of Books', 'http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2014/dec/04/question-edward-snowden/', 'The undeclared subject of "Citizenfour" is integrity—the insistence by an individual that his life and the principle he lives by should be all of a piece. Something resembling an aesthetic correlative of that integrity can be found in the documentary style of Laura Poitras.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(217, 1, 91, 3, NULL, 0, 11, 'Turner at twilight', 'Jenny Uglow, The New York Review of Books', 'http://www.nybooks.com/blogs/nyrblog/2014/nov/13/turner-at-twilight/', 'At sixty, Turner was both admired and ridiculed, his work leaving critics and spectators baffled and sometimes angry. Many saw his shimmering canvases as a crazed denial of familiar rules. Was his eyesight failing? Was he going mad? Tate Britain’s "Late Turner: Painting Set Free" is a fittingly autumnal show. Seeing the exhibition with Mike Leigh’s film "Mr. Turner" is like watching a strange, exhilarating conversation.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(218, 1, 161, 36, NULL, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Sincerest forms of flattery for British shows', 'Snobs may sneer that the series could more accurately be called "Remains of the Gosford/Upstairs/Brideshead Revisited Park." But there are times when a sincere imitation is not only better than nothing--it''s nearly as good.', 'Alessandra Stanley, The New York Times', 'Sincerest Forms of Flattery for British Shows'),
(219, 1, 161, 36, NULL, 0, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Abbey that jumped the shark', 'If you feel from time to time that the television series is attempting to enlist your sympathy for a cause that, in your own life, might rank as a low priority (the perpetuation of a gigantic nineteenth-century house and estate)—that is indeed the case.', 'James Fenton, The New York Review of Books', 'http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2012/mar/08/abbey-jumped-shark/?pagination=false'),
(220, 1, 161, 36, NULL, 0, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '“Downton Abbey"’s right-wing worldview', 'In the show’s moral universe, all that was good about a system in which the poor were trapped into servitude for the rich remains good. All that was bad floats away and is not worth portraying.', 'Daniel D''Addario, salon.com', 'http://www.salon.com/2014/01/19/downton_abbeys_right_wing_worldview_benevolent_rich_people_caring_for_servants/'),
(221, 1, 30, 3, NULL, 0, 8, 'Wes Anderson on using throwback ratios, romantic worldviews, and European reconnaissance to craft "The Grand Budapest Hotel"', 'Filmmaker Magazine', 'http://filmmakermagazine.com/84877-wes-anderson-on-using-throwback-ratios-romantic-worldviews-and-european-reconnaissance-to-craft-the-grand-budapest-hotel/', 'For all the ways his work speaks to today’s Generation Irony, Wes Anderson is an unmistakable romantic — a man who grew up with a great love of classics, be they in the realms of cinema, literature or art.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(222, 1, 138, 3, NULL, 0, 10, 'Ida''s Bittersweet Success: An Interview With Pawel Pawlikowski', 'David Sims, The Atlantic', 'http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/02/pawel-pawlikowski-on-the-personal-and-the-historical-in-ida/385568/', 'The director of the Oscar-nominated drama talks about its tribute to 60s Polish culture and the furor it generated over historical accuracy.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(223, 1, 161, 36, NULL, 0, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The most happy Fellowes', '“What I remember is, of the 60s people, the ones who went on believing were casualties…The ones who really thought the world had changed and it was all going to be flowers in our hair—it was hard for them because, by the 80s, it was absolutely clear that almost nothing had changed, except people didn’t change for dinner. That was about it.”', 'Vanity Fair', 'http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2012/12/julian-fellowes-downton-abbey'),
(224, 1, 161, 36, NULL, 0, 5, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Hugh Bonneville: escape from Downton', 'How did Hugh Bonneville become the poster-boy of period drama?', 'The Guardian', 'http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/dec/19/hugh-bonneville-poirot-downton-abbey\n'),
(225, 1, 160, 36, NULL, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The aristocrats: The graphic arts of “Game of Thrones”', 'The show’s most graphic elements—the cruel ones, the fantasy ones, and the cruel-fantasy ones—speak to female as well as male viewers. But there is something troubling about this sea of C.G.I.-perfect flesh, shaved and scentless and not especially medieval.', 'Emily Nussbaum, The New Yorker', 'http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2012/05/07/the-aristocrats?currentPage=all'),
(226, 1, 160, 36, NULL, 0, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The women and the thrones', 'What’s interesting is that the series has attracted so many viewers who wouldn’t ordinarily think of themselves as people who enjoy the fantasy genre. This has a great deal to do with the complex satisfactions of Martin’s novels, whose plots, characterization, and overall tone the series reproduces with remarkable fidelity—and whose mission is, if anything, to question and reformulate certain clichés of the fantasy/adventure genre about gender and power.', 'Daniel Mendelsohn, The New York Review of Books', 'http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2013/nov/07/women-and-thrones/'),
(227, 1, 160, 36, NULL, 0, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'George R.R. Martin: The complete Rolling Stone interview', '"Going back to Vietnam, for me the cognitive dissonance came in when I realized that Ho Chi Minh actually wasn''t Sauron. Do you remember the poster during that time? What if they gave a war and nobody came? That''s one of the fundamental questions here."', 'Rolling Stone Magazine', 'http://www.rollingstone.com/tv/news/george-r-r-martin-the-complete-rolling-stone-interview-20140613'),
(228, 1, 160, 36, NULL, 0, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'George R. R. Martin webchat transcript', '"We have ten hours and that''s [all] we have. You cannot put every line of dialogue, every incident, in the TV show. You have to cut to the chase. I do rather wish we had more than 10 hours. Not a lot more: 12 hours per season would be ideal."', 'empireonline.com', 'http://www.empireonline.com/interviews/interview.asp?IID=1496'),
(229, 1, 167, 36, NULL, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '"Homeland" and "The Manchurian Candidate"', 'The series turns the mid-century American fear of a sleeper agent on its head. Brody is not a sleeper. He is a loyal soldier who comes to feel empathy for—and solidarity with—his captor.', 'Erin Overbey, The New Yorker', 'http://www.newyorker.com/books/double-take/homeland-and-the-manchurian-candidate'),
(230, 1, 167, 36, NULL, 0, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Israeli Inspiration for "Homeland"', 'While the U.S. version focused mostly on the fraught relationship between Brody and Carrie, the Israeli version centered around issues that had been seen as taboo in a country that places the return of its captured soldiers at the top of its political agenda.”', 'Ruth Margalit, The New Yorker', 'http://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/the-israeli-inspiration-for-homeland'),
(231, 1, 167, 36, NULL, 0, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '"Homeland" is brilliant drama. But does it present a crude image of Muslims?', 'The slick US drama, now into its second series on Channel 4, draws praise from critics and viewers, but its ridiculous view of Arabs and Islam is a distortion of Middle Eastern realities.', 'Peter Beaumont, The Guardian', 'http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/oct/13/homeland-drama-offensive-portrayal-islam-arabs'),
(232, 1, 167, 36, NULL, 0, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TV’s most Islamophobic show', 'With its portraits of Brody and Roya Hammad, "Homeland" warns that Muslims are a hidden danger to fellow Americans.', 'Laila Al-Arian, salon.com', 'http://www.salon.com/2012/12/15/tvs_most_islamophobic_show/'),
(233, 1, 167, 36, NULL, 0, 5, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '"Homeland" is obviously anti-Semitic', 'Part of the genius of "Homeland" is that by making an All-American war hero into a terrorist, it does exactly the opposite of what Laila Al-Arian condemns: "Homeland" challenges the stereotypes of who is a terrorist.', 'Zach Novetsky, Tablet Magazine', 'http://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/119607/homeland-is-obviously-anti-semitic'),
(234, 1, 167, 36, NULL, 0, 6, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '"Homeland" is anything but Islamophobic', 'Despite accusations from critics and scholars, the show doesn''t reinforce stereotypes about "good" Americans and "evil" Arabs and Muslims—it challenges them.', 'Yair Rosenberg, The Atlantic', 'http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2012/12/homeland-is-anything-but-islamophobic/266418/'),
(235, 1, 167, 36, NULL, 0, 7, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Gideon Raff on creating "Homeland," his hopes for peace and "No Nuclear Iran"', '“We realized that a big difference between the Israeli audience and the American audience is that this is a huge, huge topic in Israel. It''s almost a taboo."', 'The Wrap', 'http://www.thewrap.com/tv/column-post/how-homeland-started-qa-gideon-raff-whos-israeli-series-inspired-it-58346/'),
(236, 1, 167, 36, NULL, 0, 8, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Interview Magazine: Dustin Hoffman interviews Claire Danes', '“They had written Carrie as bipolar without even knowing it…at first, I was concerned that it would just be a gimmick."', 'Interview Magazine', 'http://www.interviewmagazine.com/culture/claire-danes#_'),
(237, 1, 19, 36, NULL, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Lockdown', 'For all its daffy, dirty ways, “Orange Is the New Black” is more strongly rooted in the real world...it intends to illuminate injustice by using stories so bright that you can’t ignore them.', 'Emily Nussbaum, The New Yorker', 'http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/07/07/lockdown-2'),
(238, 1, 19, 36, NULL, 0, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'No time off for good behavior', 'Is it a problem that “Orange Is the New Black” essentially treats prison like a bad day in high school, the kind that includes both a scary walk to the principal’s office and an embarrassing visit to the school nurse?', 'Mike Hale, The New York Times', 'http://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/06/arts/television/review-orange-is-the-new-black-season-2.html'),
(239, 1, 19, 36, NULL, 0, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '"Orange Is The New Black" spreads empathy in all directions', 'Whatever flaws "Orange Is The New Black" possesses are ultimately minor and pale in comparison to the series’ epic, novelistic sweep.', 'Todd VanDerWerff, The A.V. Club', 'http://www.avclub.com/review/orange-new-black-spreads-empathy-all-directions-205601'),
(240, 1, 19, 36, NULL, 0, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Why you should watch "Orange Is the New Black"', 'Did Netflix just create the greatest lesbian TV series ever?', 'Diane Anderson-Minshall, advocate.com', 'http://www.advocate.com/print-issue/current-issue/2013/07/10/why-you-should-watch-orange-new-black?page=full'),
(241, 1, 19, 36, NULL, 0, 5, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Subversive Netflix prison drama proves addictive', 'Creator Jenji Kohan has created an alternately sly and sad pressure cooker that offers an enticing range of complicated relationships and unstable power dynamics. ', 'Maureen Ryan, The Huffington Post', 'http://www.huffingtonpost.com/maureen-ryan/orange-is-the-new-black_b_3574249.html'),
(242, 1, 111, 3, NULL, 0, 6, '"Foxcatcher"', 'History vs Hollywood', 'http://www.historyvshollywood.com/reelfaces/foxcatcher/', 'True story of "Foxcatcher" vs. Hollywood', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(243, 1, 62, 3, NULL, 0, 6, 'It’s a classic revisionist western, and one of Eastwood’s finest', 'Alex Trimble Young, salon.com', 'http://www.salon.com/2015/02/19/american_sniper_is_not_a_war_movie_its_a_classic_revisionist_western_and_one_of_eastwoods_finest/', '“American Sniper’s” harshest critics have neglected the nuances of its plot and camera work in order to discredit the film’s humanization of Kyle. They have largely done so by focusing on the divergence between the Kyle of the film and the Kyle of the ghostwritten memoir. That these critiques treat a carefully engineered Harper Collins bestseller as an authentic account of its putative author’s inner life is rather remarkable.  ', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(244, 1, 105, 3, NULL, 0, 9, 'What we Know About Paul Thomas Anderson''s "Inherent Vice"', 'Charles Bramesco, The Dissolve', 'https://thedissolve.com/news/3378-dossier-a-comprehensive-guide-to-what-we-know-abou/', 'Case file of Paul Thomas Anderson''s new film "Inherent Vice"', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(245, 1, 170, 36, NULL, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'It’s different for "Girls"', 'Why Lena Dunham''s "Girls" is like nothing else on TV', 'New York Magazine', 'http://nymag.com/arts/tv/features/girls-lena-dunham-2012-4/index1.html'),
(246, 1, 170, 36, NULL, 0, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '"Girls" has grown up - and isn''t as funny', 'How Lena Dunham''s show went from a coming-of-age story to a comedy of manners', 'Laura Bennett, The New Republic', 'http://www.newrepublic.com/article/116152/girls-season-three-review-adulthood-isnt-so-funny'),
(247, 1, 170, 36, NULL, 0, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Hannah Barbaric', 'When there’s a tiny aperture for women’s stories, when almost no women are Hollywood directors, when few women write TV shows, of course it’s the privileged ones who get traction.', 'Emily Nussbaum, The New Yorker', 'http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2013/02/11/hannah-barbaric'),
(248, 1, 170, 36, NULL, 0, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Lena Dunham’s body-image problem', 'Why "Girls"’ efforts to change cultural expectations of women are doomed.', 'Betsy Woodruff, National Review', 'http://www.nationalreview.com/article/368793/lena-dunhams-body-image-problem-betsy-woodruff'),
(249, 1, 170, 36, NULL, 0, 5, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Interview: Lena Dunham by Claire Danes', '“It''s really important to me to make work that feels socially responsible."', 'Interview Magazine', 'http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/lena-dunham-1/'),
(250, 1, 170, 36, NULL, 0, 6, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '"People called me fat and hideous, and I lived"', 'The uncontested queen of angst, Lena Dunham has made an art form of self-abasement. As her TV show "Girls" returns for a third series, Simon Hattenstone asks, does all the unflattering exposure, you know, help?', 'The Guardian', 'http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2014/jan/11/lena-dunham-called-fat-hideous-and-i-lived'),
(251, 1, 170, 36, NULL, 0, 7, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Lena Dunham addresses criticism aimed at "Girls"', '“This show isn''t supposed to feel exclusionary. It''s supposed to feel honest, and it''s supposed to feel true to many aspects of my experience."', 'NPR', 'http://www.npr.org/2012/05/07/152183865/lena-dunham-addresses-criticism-aimed-at-girls'),
(252, 1, 173, 36, NULL, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'After 19 months, Louie’s back and as good as ever', 'The defining motif of the series is a medium shot of Louie’s face, head askew, looking totally befuddled by the world.', 'Brandon Nowalk, The A.V. Club', 'http://www.avclub.com/review/after-19-months-louies-back-and-good-ever-204066'),
(253, 1, 173, 36, NULL, 0, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Life after divorce (don’t ask about the monkeys)', 'One of the problems with the show is that so much of it echoes familiar comic works.', 'Alessandra Stanley, The New York Times', 'http://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/29/arts/television/29louie.html'),
(254, 1, 173, 36, NULL, 0, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The joke’s on Louis C.K.', '"My show owes its success to other things. Larry David, Jerry Seinfeld, Garry Shandling, John Waters, Woody Allen — my show has a lot of those people’s DNA in it."', 'The New York Times', 'http://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/07/arts/for-louis-c-k-the-jokes-on-him.html'),
(255, 1, 173, 36, NULL, 0, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Louis C.K. is America''s undisputed king of comedy', 'Discomfort underlies all of C.K.''s work—it''s often both medium and message—and he seems to regard it as a moral imperative.', 'GQ Magazine', 'http://www.gq.com/entertainment/celebrities/201405/louis-ck-cover-story-may-2014'),
(256, 1, 70, 3, NULL, 0, 10, 'The Anti-Salieri? Or a Musical Travis Bickle? Another Read On “Whiplash”', 'Noah Millman, The American Conservative', 'http://www.theamericanconservative.com/millman/the-anti-salieri-or-a-musical-travis-bickle-another-read-on-whiplash/', 'The heart of our debate relates to the question of subjectivity. “Whiplash” stays very close to its protagonist – we’re seeing the world through his eyes - but it doesn’t hold our hands.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(257, 1, 178, 36, NULL, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '“Parks and Recreation”: TV’s most progressive show', 'The NBC sitcom is just as ardent in its defense of government as it is fearless in its skewering of conservatives.', 'salon.com', 'http://www.salon.com/2013/04/25/is_parks_and_recreation_secretly_socialist_partner/'),
(258, 1, 178, 36, NULL, 0, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'You really should be watching "Parks and Recreation"', 'How the NBC sitcom found its voice. Plus: its mustachioed secret weapon.', 'slate.com', 'http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/culturebox/2009/12/you_really_should_be_watching_parks_and_recreation.html'),
(259, 1, 178, 36, NULL, 0, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Making bureaucracy work: How NBC''s "Parks and Recreation" overcame bad buzz', 'In the face of bad buzz and with a little perseverance, "Parks and Recreation" executive producers Greg Daniels and Michael Schur have changed minds about their Amy Poehler comedy, once seen as a knock-off of "The Office." Now, critics are raving.', 'The Los Angeles Times', 'http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2009/11/parks-and-recreation.html'),
(260, 1, 178, 36, NULL, 0, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '"Parks and Recreation" gets political: Amy Poehler and Mike Schur talk Pawnee Debate Night', '"It’s certainly not apolitical," said Schur, who noted that Leslie "believes that government can do good things, and that’s generally speaking, a Democratic idea."', 'The Huffington Post', 'http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/04/25/parks-and-recreation-debate_n_1452848.html'),
(261, 1, 178, 36, NULL, 0, 5, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Amy Poehler of "Parks and Recreation": "I’m a lot lazier" than Leslie Knope', '"I’ve said this before, but most people’s experience with government is on a micro-level. It’s not on a macro-level. The press is so obsessed with our macro-government, with our presidential elections, with our, you know, our personality clashes between senators. But our day-to-day involvement with government is our local city council."', 'The Washington Post', 'http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/celebritology/post/amy-poehler-of-parks-and-recreation-im-a-lot-lazier-than-leslie-knope/2012/04/27/gIQAbFW4kT_blog.html'),
(262, 1, 178, 36, NULL, 0, 6, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '"Parks and Recreation" season 7 damages one legacy to elevate another', '"Parks and Rec" was always fiercely optimistic, pushing a positive agenda built on two main themes that would eventually establish its legacy: feminism and small town pride. Yet that legacy was tarnished as the show''s progressive ideals were honored while its heroically "small" home was martyred for the cause.', 'IndieWire', 'http://www.indiewire.com/article/review-parks-and-recreation-season-7-damages-one-legacy-to-elevate-another-20150225'),
(263, 1, 178, 36, NULL, 0, 7, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Amy Poehler: "It''s kind of ruined me for anything else."', 'Looking back over seven seasons of Leslie Knope.', 'HitFix', 'http://www.hitfix.com/whats-alan-watching/parks-and-recreation-star-amy-poehler-its-kind-of-ruined-me-for-anything-else/'),
(264, 1, 178, 36, NULL, 0, 8, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'You go big or you go home', 'An oral history of the creation and evolution of "Parks And Recreation"', 'Uproxx', 'http://uproxx.com/tv/2015/02/parks-and-recreation-evolution-oral-history/');
INSERT INTO `exp_matrix_data` (`row_id`, `site_id`, `entry_id`, `field_id`, `var_id`, `is_draft`, `row_order`, `col_id_1`, `col_id_2`, `col_id_3`, `col_id_4`, `col_id_5`, `col_id_6`, `col_id_7`, `col_id_8`) VALUES
(265, 1, 181, 36, NULL, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '"Mad Men" minus the racist, sexist parts', 'From Oprah to Banana Republic, pop culture is nostalgic for a dark time. Screw history, bring on the pencil skirts.', 'salon.com', 'http://www.salon.com/2009/09/23/mad_men_oprah/'),
(266, 1, 181, 36, NULL, 0, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'New "Mad Men" TV show uses the past to reveal racism and sexism of today', 'Just as science fiction often uses a future world to say things about the present you can''t say directly, his show uses the overtly sexist and racist atmosphere of a 1960 New York advertising office to talk about issues that persist today but that we are too "polite" to talk about openly.', 'alternet.org', 'http://www.alternet.org/print/story/60278/new_%22mad_men%22_tv_show_uses_the_past_to_reveal_racism_and_sexism_of_today'),
(267, 1, 181, 36, NULL, 0, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The very bright future of "Mad Men"’s Elisabeth Moss', 'As we, the audience, are preparing for a post–"Mad Men" age, so is Moss, and she’s much further along than we are.', 'vulture.com', 'http://www.vulture.com/2014/03/elisabeth-moss-on-mad-mens-final-season.html'),
(268, 1, 181, 36, NULL, 0, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The "Mad Men" account', 'Just what in the world of the show do we want to possess? The clothes and furniture? The wicked behavior? The unpunished crassness? To my mind, it’s something else entirely, something unexpected and, in a way, almost touching.', 'The New York Review of Books', 'http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2011/feb/24/mad-men-account/?pagination=false&printpage=true'),
(269, 1, 181, 36, NULL, 0, 5, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'NPR interview: Matthew Weiner', '"Mad Men" creator Matthew Weiner on the end of Don Draper’s journey', 'NPR', 'http://www.npr.org/2014/05/01/308608611/mad-men-creator-matthew-weiner-on-the-end-of-don-drapers-journey'),
(270, 1, 182, 3, NULL, 0, 1, '35 years later, "Taxi Driver" still stuns', 'J. Hoberman, The Village Voice', 'http://www.villagevoice.com/2011-03-16/film/35-years-later-taxi-driver-still-stuns/', 'Some motion pictures produce the uncanny sensation of returning the spectator’s gaze. Martin Scorsese’s "Taxi Driver" - a movie in which the most celebrated line asks the audience, ‘Are you talkin’ to me?’ - is one such film. It came, it saw, it zapped the body politic right between the eyes.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(271, 1, 182, 3, NULL, 0, 2, 'Hell on wheels', 'Jonathan Rosenbaum, The Chicago Reader', 'http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/hell-on-wheels/Content?oid=889883', 'Perhaps the most formally ravishing - as well as the most morally and ideologically problematic - film ever directed by Martin Scorsese, "Taxi Driver" remains a disturbing landmark for the kind of voluptuous doublethink it helped ratify and extend in American movies.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(272, 1, 182, 3, NULL, 0, 3, 'Interview with Martin Scorsese and Paul Schrader, March 7, 1976', 'The Chicago Sun-Times', 'http://www.rogerebert.com/interviews/interview-with-martin-scorsese', '"The goddess-whore complex. You''re raised to worship women, but you don''t know how to approach them on a human level, on a sexual level. That''s the thing with Travis, the DeNiro character - the taxi driver."', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(273, 1, 182, 3, NULL, 0, 4, 'Paul Schrader: “I was in a bad place.”', 'The Guardian', 'http://www.theguardian.com/film/2006/jul/06/features.geoffreymacnab', 'Paul Schrader was 26 and destitute when he wrote "Taxi Driver." As the film is re-released, he tells Geoffrey Macnab why he''s still proud of his violent movie - and why he lied about it to the FBI.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(274, 1, 183, 3, NULL, 0, 1, 'California burning', 'J. Hoberman, The Village Voice', 'http://www.villagevoice.com/2007-12-18/film/california-burning/full/', 'By the time the closing words "There Will Be Blood" appear (with a burst of Brahms) inscribed in heavy gothic letters on the screen, Anderson''s movie has come to seem an Old Testament story of cosmic comeuppance and filicidal madness—American history glimpsed through the smoke and fire that the lightning left behind.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(275, 1, 183, 3, NULL, 0, 2, 'An American primitive, forged in a crucible of blood and oil', 'Manohla Dargis, The New York Times', 'http://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/26/movies/26bloo.html?ref=movies&_r=0', 'This is Mr. Anderson’s fifth feature and it proves a breakthrough for him as a filmmaker. Although there are more differences than similarities between it and the Sinclair book, the novel has provided him with something he has lacked in the past, a great theme.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(276, 1, 183, 3, NULL, 0, 3, 'The new frontier’s man: Daniel Day-Lewis', 'The New York Times', 'http://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/11/magazine/11daylewis-t2.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0', '“I was deeply unsettled by the script…For me, that is a sure sign. If you remain unsettled by a piece of writing, it means you are not watching the story from the outside; you’ve already taken a step toward it."', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(277, 1, 183, 3, NULL, 0, 4, 'The A.V. Club: Paul Thomas Anderson', 'The A.V. Club', 'http://www.avclub.com/article/paul-thomas-anderson-2120', '“I didn''t even really feel like I was adapting a book. I was just desperate to find stuff to write. I can remember the way that my desk looked, with so many different scraps of paper and books about the oil industry in the early 20th century, mixed in with pieces of other scripts that I''d written. Everything was coming from so many different sources. But the book was a great stepping-stone."', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(278, 1, 183, 3, NULL, 0, 5, 'Blood for oil', 'American Cinematographer', 'https://www.theasc.com/ac_magazine/January2008/ThereWillBeBlood/page1.php', 'Robert Elswit, ASC reteams with director Paul Thomas Anderson on "There Will Be Blood," the saga of an unsociable oil prospector who strikes it rich but loses his soul.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(279, 1, 184, 3, NULL, 0, 1, 'Light years', 'Kent Jones, Film Comment', 'http://www.filmcomment.com/entry/light-years-kent-jones-tree-of-life-review', 'Malick really is making an attempt—or to put it in punitive blogspeak, “presuming”— to tell the story of us all.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(280, 1, 184, 3, NULL, 0, 2, 'Cannes 2011: "The Tree of Life"', 'J. Hoberman, The Village Voice', 'http://www.voicefilm.com/2011/05/cannes_2011_the_tree_of_life.php', '"The Tree of Life" is less profound than profoundly eccentric, while too solemn, pompous, and genteel to be truly crazy. The movie disengages the mind, even as it dulls the senses.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(281, 1, 184, 3, NULL, 0, 3, 'The Guardian: Interview with Brad Pitt', 'The Guardian', 'http://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/jun/30/brad-pitt-interview-terrence-malick', '"Perhaps we don''t need these religious concoctions to pillow the fear of death. Just the fact that there is an unknown, and something greater, can bring a feeling of peace. That''s enough for me."', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(282, 1, 184, 3, NULL, 0, 4, 'Emmanuel Lubezki, ASC, AMC creates emotionally resonant imagery for Terrence Malick’s “The Tree of Life”', 'American Cinematographer', 'http://www.theasc.com/ac_magazine/August2011/TheTreeofLife/page1.php', '“When you put someone in front of a window, you’re getting the reflection from the blue sky and the clouds and the sun bouncing on the grass and in the room. You’re getting all these colors and a different quality of light. It’s very hard to go back to artificial light in the same movie. It’s like you’re setting a tone, and artificial light feels weird and awkward [after that].”', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(283, 1, 185, 3, NULL, 0, 1, 'The New York Times: Movie Review, January 31, 1964', 'Bosley Crowther, The New York Times', 'http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=EE05E7DF173DE367BC4950DFB766838F679EDE', '“Stanley Kubrick''s new film is beyond any question the most shattering sick joke I''ve ever come across…My reaction to it is quite divided, because there is so much about it that is grand, so much that is brilliant and amusing, and much that is grave and dangerous.”', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(284, 1, 185, 3, NULL, 0, 2, 'Just what the doctor ordered: Cold War purging, political dissent and the right hand of "Dr. Strangelove"', 'Jeremy Boxen, visual-memory.co.uk', 'http://www.visual-memory.co.uk/amk/doc/0029.html', '"Dr. Strangelove" represents to the United States a purging of Cold War rhetoric and anxiety and the beginning of the wave of political and cultural dissent that would climax in the late 1960s.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(285, 1, 185, 3, NULL, 0, 3, 'Almost everything in "Dr. Strangelove" was true', 'The New Yorker', 'http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/newsdesk/2014/01/strangelove-for-real.html', 'Kubrick’s black comedy provided a far more accurate description of the dangers inherent in nuclear command-and-control systems than the ones that the American people got from the White House, the Pentagon, and the mainstream media.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(286, 1, 185, 3, NULL, 0, 4, 'Check-up with "Dr. Strangelove"', 'Filmmaker Magazine', 'http://www.filmmakermagazine.com/archives/issues/fall2004/line_items/strangelove.php#.U6ooHf3Q79c', 'Terry Southern''s unpublished profile of Stanley Kubrick for Esquire magazine', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(287, 1, 185, 3, NULL, 0, 5, 'November 27, 1965: A rare recording of Stanley Kubrick’s most revealing Interview', 'brainpickings.org', 'http://www.brainpickings.org/index.php/2013/11/27/jeremy-bernstein-stanley-kubrick-interview/', '“People react primarily to direct experience and not to abstractions; it is very rare to find anyone who can become emotionally involved with an abstraction. The longer the bomb is around without anything happening, the better the job that people do in psychologically denying its existence. It has become as abstract as the fact that we are all going to die someday, which we usually do an excellent job of denying.”', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(288, 1, 186, 36, NULL, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'In defense of Liz Lemon', 'Judging from my Twitter feed, there’s been a backlash to “30 Rock” this season, particularly the character of Liz Lemon, played by Tina Fey. Liz Lemon was once our heroine...Now she’s become infantilized and dumb. She doesn’t trust her own judgment, she’s bad at her job, and there’s something awfully misogynist about all this! Liz Lemon is pathetic. Well, I can’t get on board the hate train.', 'Emily Nussbaum, The New Yorker', 'http://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/in-defense-of-liz-lemon'),
(289, 1, 186, 36, NULL, 0, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Doing the work: what ''30 Rock'' meant for women on television', 'I have never considered Liz Lemon a feminist icon of any kind, nor have I ever considered "30 Rock" especially strong when it comes to gender politics….And yet, I think it''s been one of the most important, helpful, meaningful, landscape-altering shows for women in the history of television for one simple reason: whatever the positives and negatives of the show''s voice and aesthetic, it is Tina Fey''s voice and her aesthetic, and everyone knows it.', 'Linda Holmes, NPR', 'http://www.npr.org/blogs/monkeysee/2013/01/31/170753743/doing-the-work-what-30-rock-meant-for-women-on-television'),
(290, 1, 186, 36, NULL, 0, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '"30 Rock" character study: why Tina Fey and Alec Baldwin''s friendship-with-benefits worked', 'The improbable bond between Fey''s most popular characters infused the tart cult comedy with heart and soul; Lemon fans approved, despite Donaghy''s jerky put-downs.', 'The Hollywood Reporter', 'http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/30-rock-character-study-why-416807'),
(291, 1, 186, 36, NULL, 0, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Why Me?: Alec Baldwin’s disappointment, undimmed by success', '“Jack Donaghy is Lorne, first and foremost. ‘What am I, a farmer?’ That IS Lorne. I think he said that. Lorne’s got a tuxedo in the glove compartment of his car. Lorne is a big-ticket A-list New York water buffalo. He’s big on the Serengeti. Lorne is a person who seduces you into thinking that if you take his advice and play your cards right you’re going to end up with his life."', 'The New Yorker', 'http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2008/09/08/why-me?currentPage=1'),
(292, 1, 186, 36, NULL, 0, 5, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What Tina wants', 'Tina Fey has rules. They’ve guided the 38-year-old writer-comedian through marriage, motherhood, and a career that went into hyperdrive this fall, when her Sarah Palin impression convulsed the nation, boosting the ratings of both "Saturday Night Live" and her own NBC show, "30 Rock." Backstage at SNL, where “Palin” met Palin, and at the home Fey shares with her husband and daughter, the author reports on how a tweezer, cream rinse, a diet, and a Teutonic will transformed a mousy brain into a brainy glamour-puss.', 'Vanity Fair', 'http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/2009/01/tina_fey200901'),
(293, 1, 187, 36, NULL, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '“Veep”: “The Office” goes to D.C.', 'It’s probably helpful to think of Veep as a workplace comedy rather than a purely political one.', 'salon.com', 'http://www.salon.com/2012/04/20/the_office_goes_to_d_c/'),
(294, 1, 187, 36, NULL, 0, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Pol watchers: everyone’s a bad guy', 'It is no accident that "Veep" is an Americanized version of "The Thick of It," just as "House of Cards," the Netflix series about ambition and corruption in the nation’s capital, is an adaptation of a BBC series by the same name.', 'The New York Times', 'http://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/14/arts/television/pol-watchers-everyones-a-bad-guy.html'),
(295, 1, 187, 36, NULL, 0, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '"Veep" creator Armando Iannucci on pushing TV comedy "to the edge of a cliff"', 'The British satirist behind the HBO hit shares improv secrets, insults and behind-the-scenes tales in the latest edition of The Wrap''s Writers’ Room series.', 'The Wrap', 'http://www.thewrap.com/veep-creator-armando-iannucci-writers-room/'),
(296, 1, 187, 36, NULL, 0, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Julia Louis-Dreyfus and Nancy Pelosi: a power lunch, times two', 'Julia Louis-Dreyfus: “I think of it as spending celebrity, as Norman Lear once said. Celebrity is a kind of capital. You have to use it wisely, and you can overspend it easily. So I use it carefully, when I can, for just the right thing.”', 'The New York Times', 'http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/06/fashion/julia-louis-dreyfus-and-nancy-pelosi-a-power-lunch-times-two.html'),
(299, 1, 188, 36, NULL, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'All in the Modern Family', 'The genre has been declared dead many times, but a hit show is reviving the half-hour TV comedy with a combination of edge, quirkiness—and family values.', 'The Wall Street Journal', 'http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052748704240004575085590627459182'),
(300, 1, 188, 36, NULL, 0, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Variety review: ‘Modern Family’', 'Easily the new season’s best comedy pilot, “Modern Family” deftly serves up laughs on multiple levels while actually making a point about the evolving nature of what constitutes “family.”', 'Variety', 'http://variety.com/2009/tv/reviews/modern-family-1200476044/'),
(298, 1, 178, 36, NULL, 0, 9, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'How "Parks and Recreation" found all-time greatness in simple goodness', 'A classic of the form defined by its indomitable heroine.', 'HitFix', 'http://www.hitfix.com/whats-alan-watching/how-parks-and-recreation-found-all-time-greatness-in-simple-goodness'),
(301, 1, 188, 36, NULL, 0, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '“Modern Family” is a class-blind fantasy world', 'The show makes a point of drawing out differences in outlook between the older couple, the younger couple and the gay couple — and yet all of them are able to afford keeping a parent home full-time, and none of them seem ever to meet anyone unlike them out in the world.', 'salon.com', 'http://www.salon.com/2013/09/24/modern_family_is_a_class_blind_fantasy_world/'),
(302, 1, 188, 36, NULL, 0, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Keeping up with the Pritchetts: behind the scenes on "Modern Family"', 'Since "Modern Family" began nearly four years ago, it has won nearly every sitcom award going. It''s the sitcom for everyone, in an age when comedy with that kind of broad appeal has long-since been proclaimed dead.', 'GQ', 'http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/entertainment/articles/2013-04/12/modern-family-hit-comedy-cast-creator-interviews/viewall'),
(303, 1, 188, 36, NULL, 0, 5, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Family man: showrunner Steve Levitan\n', '"It was a matter of populating it with multiple families, and the idea was, how has family changed recently?"', 'deadline.com', 'http://www.deadline.com/2010/08/modern-family-showrunner-steve-levitan/'),
(304, 1, 189, 3, NULL, 0, 1, 'A free replay (notes on "Vertigo")', 'chrismarker.org', 'http://chrismarker.org/chris-marker/a-free-replay-notes-on-vertigo/', 'English translation of Chris Marker''s celebrated essay on his favorite film.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(305, 1, 189, 3, NULL, 0, 2, 'Puzzling over "Vertigo"', 'Geoff Andrew, The British Film Institute', 'http://www.bfi.org.uk/news/puzzling-over-vertigo', 'As Hitchcock’s "Vertigo" is rereleased nationwide, Geoff Andrew ponders the steady rise in critical esteem of a cruel and complex film now considered the ‘greatest ever made.''', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(306, 1, 190, 3, NULL, 0, 1, 'Film-makers on film: Peter Bogdanovich', 'Telegraph', 'http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmmakersonfilm/3618071/Film-makers-on-film-Peter-Bogdanovich.html', 'Peter Bogdanovich talks to Sheila Johnston about Orson Welles'' "Citizen Kane" (1941)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(307, 1, 190, 3, NULL, 0, 2, '"Citizen Kane" a masterpiece at 50 (1991)', 'Roger Ebert, The Chicago Sun-Times', 'http://www.rogerebert.com/rogers-journal/citizen-kane-a-masterpiece-at-50', 'Orson Welles had made what would eventually become known as the greatest movie of all time. But he was having trouble getting it released.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(308, 1, 191, 3, NULL, 0, 1, 'American obsession', 'J. Hoberman, The New York Times', 'http://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/24/books/review/the-searchers-by-glenn-frankel.html?pagewanted=all', 'There are a few Hollywood movies so thematically rich and so historically resonant they may be considered part of American literature. “The Searchers” is one.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(309, 1, 191, 3, NULL, 0, 2, 'Searching for John Ford', 'Jonathan Rosenbaum, Cineaste', 'http://www.jonathanrosenbaum.net/2001/10/review-of-searching-for-john-ford-tk/', 'Most previous writing on Ford has been hamstrung by opting for either ideological attack or ideological defense and then becoming entrenched in that one-eyed position. McBride, by refreshing contrast, has the good sense to perceive that "The Searchers" is a racist film that also has profound and objective things to say about racism — sometimes in alternation and sometimes even simultaneously.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(310, 1, 192, 3, NULL, 0, 1, '"Breathless" then and now', 'Dudley Andrew, The Criterion Collection', 'http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/526-breathless-then-and-now', '"Breathless" is one of Godard’s (and our culture’s) reflex images, so acute and apt that it remains sharply in focus for anyone who cares about the cinema, about the West in 1960, or about ourselves at the onset of the twenty-first century.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(311, 1, 192, 3, NULL, 0, 2, '“Breathless”: Rebel postcard from the past', 'Andrew O''Hehir, salon.com', 'http://www.salon.com/2010/05/29/breathless/', 'Godard''s smirking gangster romance, shot on the 1960 streets of Paris, changed the world -- and all of us', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(312, 1, 193, 3, NULL, 0, 1, '"2001: A Space Odyssey" - Chicago Sun-Times Review, April 12, 1968', 'Roger Ebert, The Chicago Sun-Times', 'http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/2001-a-space-odyssey-1968', 'It was e. e. cummings, the poet, who said he''d rather learn from one bird how to sing than teach 10,000 stars how not to dance. I imagine cummings would not have enjoyed Stanley Kubrick''s "2001: A Space Odyssey," in which stars dance but birds do not sing. The fascinating thing about this film is that it fails on the human level but succeeds magnificently on a cosmic scale.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(313, 1, 193, 3, NULL, 0, 2, 'Masterpiece: “2001: A Space Odyssey”', 'Brian Libby, salon.com', 'http://www.salon.com/2002/03/05/2001_3/', 'With music and mind-blowing visuals, Stanley Kubrick created a wildly popular avant-garde film that asked all of the biggest questions -- without venturing any easy answers.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(314, 1, 193, 3, NULL, 0, 3, 'An interview with Stanley Kubrick (1969)', 'visual-memory.co.uk', 'http://www.visual-memory.co.uk/amk/doc/0069.html', '"One of the things we were trying to convey in this part of the film is the reality of a world populated -- as ours soon will be -- by machine entities who have as much, or more, intelligence as human beings, and who have the same emotional potentialities in their personalities as human beings. We wanted to stimulate people to think what it would be like to share a planet with such creatures.”', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(315, 1, 193, 3, NULL, 0, 4, 'The Playboy interview: Stanley Kubrick (1968)', 'Playboy Magazine', 'http://paulnahm.blogspot.com/2010/06/playboy-interview-wstanley-kubrick-in.html', '“I don’t believe in any of Earth’s monotheistic religions, but I do believe that one can construct an intriguing scientific definition of God, once you accept the fact that there are approximately 100 billion stars in our galaxy alone, that each star is a life-giving sun and that there are approximately 100 billion galaxies in just the visible universe."', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(316, 1, 194, 3, NULL, 0, 1, 'Roger Ebert’s The Great Movies: "Raging Bull"', 'Roger Ebert, The Chicago Sun-Times', 'http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-raging-bull-1980', '“Raging Bull" is not a film about boxing but about a man with paralyzing jealousy and sexual insecurity, for whom being punished in the ring serves as confession, penance and absolution. It is no accident that the screenplay never concerns itself with fight strategy. For Jake LaMotta, what happens during a fight is controlled not by tactics but by his fears and drives.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(317, 1, 194, 3, NULL, 0, 2, '"Raging Bull" - The New York Times review, November 14, 1980', 'Vincent Canby, The New York Times', 'http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C06E6D71238F937A25752C1A966948260\n', 'It''s exceedingly violent as well as poetic and, finally, humane in the way of unsentimental fiction that understands that a life - any life - can only be appreciated when the darkness that surrounds it is acknowledged.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(318, 1, 194, 3, NULL, 0, 3, 'Martin Scorsese: On "Raging Bull," Robert DeNiro, movies, and more', 'Word & Film', 'http://www.wordandfilm.com/2011/02/martin-scorsese-on-raging-bull-robert-de-niro-movies-and-more/', '“I saw too many of those films that came out in the fifties, or late forties, when Freudian psychology was coming in, and every movie explained everything...You can’t explain a human being with one Freudian term. On ''Raging Bull,'' I said let’s take all that out."', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(319, 1, 194, 3, NULL, 0, 4, 'Brutal attraction: The making of "Raging Bull"', 'Vanity Fair', 'http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/features/2010/03/raging-bull-201003', 'How one of Hollywood’s great friendships, forged by "Mean Streets" and "Taxi Driver," drove Scorsese’s finest film.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(320, 1, 195, 3, NULL, 0, 1, 'Roger Ebert''s The Great Movies: "8½"', 'Roger Ebert, The Chicago Sun-Times', 'http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-8-12--eight-and-a-half-1963', 'I have seen "8½" over and over again, and my appreciation only deepens. It does what is almost impossible: Fellini is a magician who discusses, reveals, explains and deconstructs his tricks, while still fooling us with them.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(321, 1, 195, 3, NULL, 0, 2, 'A film with itself as its subject', 'Alexander Sesonske, The Criterion Collection', 'http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/173-8-1-2-a-film-with-itself-as-its-subject', '"8½" is a film about making a film, and the film that is being made is "8½."', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(322, 1, 195, 3, NULL, 0, 3, 'When “he” became “I”', 'Tullio Kezich, The Criterion Collection', 'http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/172-8-1-2-when-he-became-i', 'Fellini, by recounting through "8½" the impossibility of making a movie, ended up creating a masterpiece that almost fell into his lap.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(323, 1, 195, 3, NULL, 0, 4, 'Derek Malcolm''s century of film: "8½"', 'Derek Malcolm, The Guardian', 'http://www.theguardian.com/film/1999/apr/22/derekmalcolmscenturyoffilm.derekmalcolm', '"8½" is probably the most potent movie about film-making, within which fantasy and reality are mixed without obfuscation.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(324, 1, 196, 3, NULL, 0, 1, 'The stuff of dreams', 'Jonathan Rosenbaum, The Guardian', 'http://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/jan/31/1', 'F. W. Murnau''s "Sunrise" was the film in which cinema, painting, music and literature merged - in a way that is still startling today.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(325, 1, 196, 3, NULL, 0, 2, 'Through a looking glass', 'J. Hoberman, The Village Voice', 'http://www.villagevoice.com/2004-08-31/film/through-a-looking-glass/full/', 'The ultimate cinephile magazine "Cahiers du Cinéma" declared Murnau''s first American movie "the single greatest masterwork in the history of cinema." It''s an assertion as reckless, romantic, and extravagant as the movie itself.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(326, 1, 197, 3, NULL, 0, 1, 'The quiet master', 'Peter Bradshaw, The Guardian', 'http://www.theguardian.com/film/2005/jun/10/features.peterbradshaw', 'Debates over the best film of all time tend to go no further than Hollywood classics such as "Citizen Kane." But the influential Halliwell''s Film Guide now says the title belongs to "Tokyo Story," a little-known Japanese film in which nothing much happens. Peter Bradshaw pays tribute.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(327, 1, 197, 3, NULL, 0, 2, 'Compassionate detachment', 'David Bordwell, The Criterion Collection', 'http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/301-tokyo-story-compassionate-detachment', 'In his restrained masterpiece of family life, Yasujiro Ozu makes something extraordinary from the ordinary.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(328, 1, 198, 3, NULL, 0, 1, 'Everyone has their reasons', 'Alexander Sesonske, The Criterion Collection', 'http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/308-the-rules-of-the-game-everyone-has-their-reasons', 'A dazzling accomplishment, original in form and style, a comic tragedy, absurd and profound, graced by two of the most brilliant scenes ever created.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(329, 1, 198, 3, NULL, 0, 2, 'Eve of destruction', 'Leslie Camhi, The Village Voice', 'http://www.villagevoice.com/2006-10-24/film/eve-of-destruction/full/', 'It is required viewing, if only to understand the ideal that filmmakers from Robert Altman to Woody Allen have been after. And even if you think you know it, see it again for its newly rediscovered depth of field, and even more, for its infinite wellsprings of character and empathy.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(330, 1, 205, 3, NULL, 0, 1, 'Let''s Talk About the Ending of ''Snowpiercer''', 'Lindsey Weber, Vulture.com', 'http://www.vulture.com/2014/07/snowpiecer-movie-discussion.html', 'After the Snowpiercer train makes its final crash landing (and BOOM goes the Kronole!), what happens to humanity? Does the film end with hope (as it seems to imply), or would the odds still be impossibly stacked against our final two survivors making it on their own for very long, what with that polar bear giving them the big eye?', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(331, 1, 205, 3, NULL, 0, 2, 'Director Bong Joon-ho Breaks Down ''Snowpiercer''s Ending', 'Simon Abrams, Vulture.com', 'http://www.vulture.com/2014/06/director-bong-joon-ho-talks-snowpiercers-ending.html', 'Snowpiercer, South Korean filmmaker Bong Joon-ho''s liberal adaptation of the French comic book of the same name, looks at the survivors of a population-decimating crisis trapped in the title train by fierce sub-Arctic temperatures. Two of them, Curtis and Nam (Chris Evans and Song Kang-Ho) lead the impoverished tail section in revolt against the oppressive front cars'' aristocracy. With the help of translator Dooho Choi, Vulture talked to Bong about class warfare and Snowpiercer''s ending.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
